# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: logic-foundations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In mathematics and mathematical logic, **Boolean algebra** is a branch of algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] It differs from elementary algebra in two ways.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] First, the values of the variables are the truth values *true* and *false*, usually denoted by 1 and 0, whereas in elementary algebra the values of the variables are numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Second, Boolean algebra uses logical operators such as conjunction (*and*) denoted as ∧, disjunction (*or*) denoted as ∨, and negation (*not*) denoted as ¬.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Elementary algebra, on the other hand, uses arithmetic operators such as addition, multiplication, subtraction, and division.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boolean algebra is therefore a formal way of describing logical operations in the same way that elementary algebra describes numerical operations.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boolean algebra was introduced by George Boole in his first book *The Mathematical Analysis of Logic* (1847), and set forth more fully in his *An Investigation of the Laws of Thought* (1854).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] According to Huntington, the term *Boolean algebra* was first suggested by Henry M.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Sheffer in 1913, although Charles Sanders Peirce gave the title "A Boolian [*sic*] Algebra with One Constant" to the first chapter of his "The Simplest Mathematics" in 1880.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boolean algebra has been fundamental in the development of digital electronics, and is provided for in all modern programming languages.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] It is also used in set theory and statistics.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A precursor of Boolean algebra was Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz's algebra of concepts.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The usage of binary in relation to the *I Ching* was central to Leibniz's *characteristica universalis*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] It eventually created the foundations of algebra of concepts.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Leibniz's algebra of concepts is deductively equivalent to the Boolean algebra of sets.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boole's algebra predated the modern developments in abstract algebra and mathematical logic; it is however seen as connected to the origins of both fields.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In an abstract setting, Boolean algebra was perfected in the late 19th century by Jevons, Schröder, Huntington and others, until it reached the modern conception of an (abstract) mathematical structure.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] For example, the empirical observation that one can manipulate expressions in the algebra of sets, by translating them into expressions in Boole's algebra, is explained in modern terms by saying that the algebra of sets is *a* Boolean algebra (note the indefinite article).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Stone proved in 1936 that every Boolean algebra is isomorphic to a field of sets.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In the 1930s, while studying switching circuits, Claude Shannon observed that one could also apply the rules of Boole's algebra in this setting, and he introduced *switching algebra* as a way to analyze and design circuits by algebraic means in terms of logic gates.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Shannon already had at his disposal the abstract mathematical apparatus, thus he cast his switching algebra as the *two-element Boolean algebra*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In modern circuit engineering settings, there is little need to consider other Boolean algebras, thus "switching algebra" and "Boolean algebra" are often used interchangeably.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Efficient implementation of Boolean functions is a fundamental problem in the design of combinational logic circuits.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Modern electronic design automation tools for very-large-scale integration (VLSI) circuits often rely on an efficient representation of Boolean functions known as (reduced ordered) binary decision diagrams (BDD) for logic synthesis and formal verification.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Logic sentences that can be expressed in classical propositional calculus have an equivalent expression in Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Thus, *Boolean logic* is sometimes used to denote propositional calculus performed in this way.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boolean algebra is not sufficient to capture logic formulas using quantifiers, like those from first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Although the development of mathematical logic did not follow Boole's program, the connection between his algebra and logic was later put on firm ground in the setting of algebraic logic, which also studies the algebraic systems of many other logics.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The closely related model of computation known as a *Boolean circuit* relates time complexity (of an algorithm) to circuit complexity.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Whereas expressions denote mainly numbers in elementary algebra, in Boolean algebra, they denote the truth values *false* and *true*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] These values are represented with the bits, 0 and 1.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] They do not behave like the integers 0 and 1, for which 1 + 1 = 2, but may be identified with the elements of the two-element field GF(2), that is, integer arithmetic modulo 2, for which 1 + 1 = 0.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Addition and multiplication then play the Boolean roles of XOR (exclusive-or) and AND (conjunction), respectively, with disjunction *x* ∨ *y* (inclusive-or) definable as *x* + *y* − *xy* and negation ¬*x* as 1 − *x*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In GF(2), − may be replaced by +, since they denote the same operation; however, this way of writing Boolean operations allows applying the usual arithmetic operations of integers (this may be useful when using a programming language in which GF(2) is not implemented).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boolean algebra also deals with functions which have their values in the set {0,1}.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A sequence of bits is a commonly used example of such a function.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Another common example is the totality of subsets of a set *E*: to a subset *F* of *E*, one can define the indicator function that takes the value 1 on *F*, and 0 outside *F*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The most general example is the set elements of a Boolean algebra, with all of the foregoing being instances thereof.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] As with elementary algebra, the purely equational part of the theory may be developed, without considering explicit values for the variables.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Variables in Boolean algebra that store the logical value of 0 and 1 are called the *Boolean variables*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] They are used to store either true or false values.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] When used in expressions, the operators are applied according to the precedence rules.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] As with elementary algebra, expressions in parentheses are evaluated first, following the precedence rules.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] These definitions give rise to the following truth tables giving the values of these operations for all four possible inputs.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boolean value and there are only two choices.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] as something other than either true or false).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] (often abbreviated as XOR) to distinguish it from disjunction as the inclusive kind.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] true (e.g. see table): if both are true then result is false.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Defined in terms of arithmetic it is addition where mod 2 is 1 + 1 = 0.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A *law* of Boolean algebra is an identity such as *x* ∨ (*y* ∨ *z*) = (*x* ∨ *y*) ∨ *z* between two Boolean terms, where a *Boolean term* is defined as an expression built up from variables and the constants 0 and 1 using the operations ∧, ∨, and ¬.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The concept can be extended to terms involving other Boolean operations such as ⊕, →, and ≡, but such extensions are unnecessary for the purposes to which the laws are put.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Such purposes include the definition of a Boolean algebra as any model of the Boolean laws, and as a means for deriving new laws from old as in the derivation of *x* ∨ (*y* ∧ *z*) = *x* ∨ (*z* ∧ *y*) from *y* ∧ *z* = *z* ∧ *y* (as treated in *§ Axiomatizing Boolean algebra*).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boolean algebra satisfies many of the same laws as ordinary algebra when one matches up ∨ with addition and ∧ with multiplication.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Taking *x* = 2 in the third law above shows that it is not an ordinary algebra law, since 2 × 2 = 4.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The remaining five laws can be falsified in ordinary algebra by taking all variables to be 1.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] For example, in absorption law 1, the left hand side would be 1(1 + 1) = 2, while the right hand side would be 1 (and so on).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] All of the laws treated thus far have been for conjunction and disjunction.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] These operations have the property that changing either argument either leaves the output unchanged, or the output changes in the same way as the input.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Equivalently, changing any variable from 0 to 1 never results in the output changing from 1 to 0.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Operations with this property are said to be *monotone*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Thus the axioms thus far have all been for monotonic Boolean logic.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Nonmonotonicity enters via complement ¬ as follows.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The complement operation is defined by the following two laws.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] All properties of negation including the laws below follow from the above two laws alone.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The laws listed above define Boolean algebra, in the sense that they entail the rest of the subject.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The laws *complementation* 1 and 2, together with the monotone laws, suffice for this purpose and can therefore be taken as one possible *complete* set of laws or axiomatization of Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Every law of Boolean algebra follows logically from these axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Furthermore, Boolean algebras can then be defined as the models of these axioms as treated in *§ Boolean algebras*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Writing down further laws of Boolean algebra cannot give rise to any new consequences of these axioms, nor can it rule out any model of them.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In contrast, in a list of some but not all of the same laws, there could have been Boolean laws that did not follow from those on the list, and moreover there would have been models of the listed laws that were not Boolean algebras.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] This axiomatization is by no means the only one, or even necessarily the most natural given that attention was not paid as to whether some of the axioms followed from others, but there was simply a choice to stop when enough laws had been noticed, treated further in *§ Axiomatizing Boolean algebra*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Or the intermediate notion of axiom can be sidestepped altogether by defining a Boolean law directly as any *tautology*, understood as an equation that holds for all values of its variables over 0 and 1.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] All these definitions of Boolean algebra can be shown to be equivalent.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Principle: If *{X, R}* is a partially ordered set, then *{X, R(inverse)}* is also a partially ordered set.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] There is nothing special about the choice of symbols for the values of Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] 0 and 1 could be renamed to *α* and *β*, and as long as it was done consistently throughout, it would still be Boolean algebra, albeit with some obvious cosmetic differences.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] But suppose 0 and 1 were renamed 1 and 0 respectively.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Then it would still be Boolean algebra, and moreover operating on the same values.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] However, it would not be identical to our original Boolean algebra because now ∨ behaves the way ∧ used to do and vice versa.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] So there are still some cosmetic differences to show that the notation has been changed, despite the fact that 0s and 1s are still being used.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] But if in addition to interchanging the names of the values, the names of the two binary operations are also interchanged, *now* there is no trace of what was done.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The end product is completely indistinguishable from what was started with.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The columns for *x* ∧ *y* and *x* ∨ *y* in the truth tables have changed places, but that switch is immaterial.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] When values and operations can be paired up in a way that leaves everything important unchanged when all pairs are switched simultaneously, the members of each pair are called *dual* to each other.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Thus 0 and 1 are dual, and ∧ and ∨ are dual.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The *duality principle*, also called De Morgan duality, asserts that Boolean algebra is unchanged when all dual pairs are interchanged.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] One change not needed to make as part of this interchange was to complement.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The identity or do-nothing operation *x* (copy the input to the output) is also self-dual.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A more complicated example of a self-dual operation is (*x* ∧ *y*) ∨ (*y* ∧ *z*) ∨ (*z* ∧ *x*).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] There is no self-dual binary operation that depends on both its arguments.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A composition of self-dual operations is a self-dual operation.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] These four functions form a group under function composition, isomorphic to the Klein four-group, acting on the set of Boolean polynomials.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Walter Gottschalk remarked that consequently a more appropriate name for the phenomenon would be the *principle* (or *square*) *of quaternality*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A Venn diagram can be used as a representation of a Boolean operation using shaded overlapping regions.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] There is one region for each variable, all circular in the examples here.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The interior and exterior of region *x* corresponds respectively to the values 1 (true) and 0 (false) for variable *x*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The shading indicates the value of the operation for each combination of regions, with dark denoting 1 and light 0 (some authors use the opposite convention).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The three Venn diagrams in the figure below represent respectively conjunction *x* ∧ *y*, disjunction *x* ∨ *y*, and complement ¬*x*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] For conjunction, the region inside both circles is shaded to indicate that *x* ∧ *y* is 1 when both variables are 1.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The other regions are left unshaded to indicate that *x* ∧ *y* is 0 for the other three combinations.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The second diagram represents disjunction *x* ∨ *y* by shading those regions that lie inside either or both circles.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The third diagram represents complement ¬*x* by shading the region *not* inside the circle.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] While we have not shown the Venn diagrams for the constants 0 and 1, they are trivial, being respectively a white box and a dark box, neither one containing a circle.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] However, we could put a circle for *x* in those boxes, in which case each would denote a function of one argument, *x*, which returns the same value independently of *x*, called a constant function.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] As far as their outputs are concerned, constants and constant functions are indistinguishable; the difference is that a constant takes no arguments, called a *zeroary* or *nullary* operation, while a constant function takes one argument, which it ignores, and is a *unary* operation.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Venn diagrams are helpful in visualizing laws.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Idempotence of ∧ and ∨ can be visualized by sliding the two circles together and noting that the shaded area then becomes the whole circle, for both ∧ and ∨.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] To see the first absorption law, *x* ∧ (*x* ∨ *y*) = *x*, start with the diagram in the middle for *x* ∨ *y* and note that the portion of the shaded area in common with the *x* circle is the whole of the *x* circle.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] For the second absorption law, *x* ∨ (*x* ∧ *y*) = *x*, start with the left diagram for *x*∧*y* and note that shading the whole of the *x* circle results in just the *x* circle being shaded, since the previous shading was inside the *x* circle.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The double negation law can be seen by complementing the shading in the third diagram for ¬*x*, which shades the *x* circle.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] To visualize the first De Morgan's law, (¬*x*) ∧ (¬*y*) = ¬(*x* ∨ *y*), start with the middle diagram for *x* ∨ *y* and complement its shading so that only the region outside both circles is shaded, which is what the right hand side of the law describes.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The result is the same as if we shaded that region which is both outside the *x* circle *and* outside the *y* circle, i.e. the conjunction of their exteriors, which is what the left hand side of the law describes.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The second De Morgan's law, (¬*x*) ∨ (¬*y*) = ¬(*x* ∧ *y*), works the same way with the two diagrams interchanged.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The first complement law, *x* ∧ ¬*x* = 0, says that the interior and exterior of the *x* circle have no overlap.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The second complement law, *x* ∨ ¬*x* = 1, says that everything is either inside or outside the *x* circle.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Digital logic is the application of the Boolean algebra of 0 and 1 to electronic hardware consisting of logic gates connected to form a circuit diagram.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Each gate implements a Boolean operation, and is depicted schematically by a shape indicating the operation.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The lines on the left of each gate represent input wires or *ports*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The value of the input is represented by a voltage on the lead.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] For so-called "active-high" logic, 0 is represented by a voltage close to zero or "ground," while 1 is represented by a voltage close to the supply voltage; active-low reverses this.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The line on the right of each gate represents the output port, which normally follows the same voltage conventions as the input ports.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Complement is implemented with an inverter gate.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The triangle denotes the operation that simply copies the input to the output; the small circle on the output denotes the actual inversion complementing the input.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The convention of putting such a circle on any port means that the signal passing through this port is complemented on the way through, whether it is an input or output port.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The duality principle, or De Morgan's laws, can be understood as asserting that complementing all three ports of an AND gate converts it to an OR gate and vice versa, as shown in Figure 4 below.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Complementing both ports of an inverter however leaves the operation unchanged.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] More generally, one may complement any of the eight subsets of the three ports of either an AND or OR gate.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The resulting sixteen possibilities give rise to only eight Boolean operations, namely those with an odd number of 1s in their truth table.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] There are eight such because the "odd-bit-out" can be either 0 or 1 and can go in any of four positions in the truth table.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] There being sixteen binary Boolean operations, this must leave eight operations with an even number of 1s in their truth tables.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Two of these are the constants 0 and 1 (as binary operations that ignore both their inputs); four are the operations that depend nontrivially on exactly one of their two inputs, namely *x*, *y*, ¬*x*, and ¬*y*; and the remaining two are *x* ⊕ *y* (XOR) and its complement *x* ≡ *y*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The term "algebra" denotes both a subject, namely the subject of algebra, and an object, namely an algebraic structure.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Whereas the foregoing has addressed the subject of Boolean algebra, this section deals with mathematical objects called Boolean algebras, defined in full generality as any model of the Boolean laws.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] We begin with a special case of the notion definable without reference to the laws, namely concrete Boolean algebras, and then give the formal definition of the general notion.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A *concrete Boolean algebra* or field of sets is any nonempty set of subsets of a given set *X* closed under the set operations of union, intersection, and complement relative to *X*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] (Historically *X* itself was required to be nonempty as well to exclude the degenerate or one-element Boolean algebra, which is the one exception to the rule that all Boolean algebras satisfy the same equations since the degenerate algebra satisfies every equation.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] However, this exclusion conflicts with the preferred purely equational definition of "Boolean algebra", there being no way to rule out the one-element algebra using only equations— 0 ≠ 1 does not count, being a negated equation.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A subset *Y* of *X* can be identified with an indexed family of bits with index set *X*, with the bit indexed by *x* ∈ *X* being 1 or 0 according to whether or not *x* ∈ *Y*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] (This is the so-called characteristic function notion of a subset.) For example, a 32-bit computer word consists of 32 bits indexed by the set {0,1,2,...,31}, with 0 and 31 indexing the low and high order bits respectively.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The set {0,1} and its Boolean operations as treated above can be understood as the special case of bit vectors of length one, which by the identification of bit vectors with subsets can also be understood as the two subsets of a one-element set.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] This is called the *prototypical* Boolean algebra, justified by the following observation.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The laws satisfied by all nondegenerate concrete Boolean algebras coincide with those satisfied by the prototypical Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Certainly any law satisfied by all concrete Boolean algebras is satisfied by the prototypical one since it is concrete.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Conversely any law that fails for some concrete Boolean algebra must have failed at a particular bit position, in which case that position by itself furnishes a one-bit counterexample to that law.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Nondegeneracy ensures the existence of at least one bit position because there is only one empty bit vector.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The final goal of the next section can be understood as eliminating "concrete" from the above observation.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] That goal is reached via the stronger observation that, up to isomorphism, all Boolean algebras are concrete.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The Boolean algebras so far have all been concrete, consisting of bit vectors or equivalently of subsets of some set.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Such a Boolean algebra consists of a set and operations on that set which can be *shown* to satisfy the laws of Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Instead of showing that the Boolean laws are satisfied, we can instead postulate a set *X*, two binary operations on *X*, and one unary operation, and *require* that those operations satisfy the laws of Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The elements of *X* need not be bit vectors or subsets but can be anything at all.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] This leads to the more general *abstract* definition.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] is any set with binary operations ∧ and ∨ and a unary operation ¬ thereon satisfying the Boolean laws.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] For the purposes of this definition it is irrelevant how the operations came to satisfy the laws, whether by fiat or proof.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] All concrete Boolean algebras satisfy the laws (by proof rather than fiat), whence every concrete Boolean algebra is a Boolean algebra according to our definitions.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] This axiomatic definition of a Boolean algebra as a set and certain operations satisfying certain laws or axioms *by fiat* is entirely analogous to the abstract definitions of group, ring, field etc. characteristic of modern or abstract algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Given any complete axiomatization of Boolean algebra, such as the axioms for a complemented distributive lattice, a sufficient condition for an algebraic structure of this kind to satisfy all the Boolean laws is that it satisfy just those axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The following is therefore an equivalent definition.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The section on axiomatization lists other axiomatizations, any of which can be made the basis of an equivalent definition.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Although every concrete Boolean algebra is a Boolean algebra, not every Boolean algebra need be concrete.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Let *n* be a square-free positive integer, one not divisible by the square of an integer, for example 30 but not 12.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The operations of greatest common divisor, least common multiple, and division into *n* (that is, ¬*x* = *n*/*x*), can be shown to satisfy all the Boolean laws when their arguments range over the positive divisors of *n*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Hence those divisors form a Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] These divisors are not subsets of a set, making the divisors of *n* a Boolean algebra that is not concrete according to our definitions.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] So this example, while not technically concrete, is at least "morally" concrete via this representation, called an isomorphism.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] This example is an instance of the following notion.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] when it is isomorphic to a concrete Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The next question is answered positively as follows.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] That is, up to isomorphism, abstract and concrete Boolean algebras are the same thing.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] This result depends on the Boolean prime ideal theorem, a choice principle slightly weaker than the axiom of choice.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] This strong relationship implies a weaker result strengthening the observation in the previous subsection to the following easy consequence of representability.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The laws satisfied by all Boolean algebras coincide with those satisfied by the prototypical Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] It is weaker in the sense that it does not of itself imply representability.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boolean algebras are special here, for example a relation algebra is a Boolean algebra with additional structure but it is not the case that every relation algebra is representable in the sense appropriate to relation algebras.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The above definition of an abstract Boolean algebra as a set together with operations satisfying "the" Boolean laws raises the question of what those laws are.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A simplistic answer is "all Boolean laws", which can be defined as all equations that hold for the Boolean algebra of 0 and 1.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] However, since there are infinitely many such laws, this is not a satisfactory answer in practice, leading to the question of it suffices to require only finitely many laws to hold.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In the case of Boolean algebras, the answer is "yes": the finitely many equations listed above are sufficient.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Thus, Boolean algebra is said to be *finitely axiomatizable* or *finitely based*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Moreover, the number of equations needed can be further reduced.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] To begin with, some of the above laws are implied by some of the others.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A sufficient subset of the above laws consists of the pairs of associativity, commutativity, and absorption laws, distributivity of ∧ over ∨ (or the other distributivity law—one suffices), and the two complement laws.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In fact, this is the traditional axiomatization of Boolean algebra as a complemented distributive lattice.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] It is also possible to find longer single axioms using more conventional operations; see Minimal axioms for Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Syntactically, every Boolean term corresponds to a *propositional formula* of propositional logic.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In this translation between Boolean algebra and propositional logic, Boolean variables *x, y,* ... become *propositional variables* (or *atoms*) *P, Q*, ...
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Boolean terms such as *x* ∨ *y* become propositional formulas *P* ∨ *Q*; 0 becomes *false* or **⊥**, and 1 becomes *true* or **⊤**.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] It is convenient when referring to generic propositions to use Greek letters Φ, Ψ, ... as metavariables (variables outside the language of propositional calculus, used when talking *about* propositional calculus) to denote propositions.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The semantics of propositional logic rely on *truth assignments*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In classical semantics, only the two-element Boolean algebra is used, while in Boolean-valued semantics arbitrary Boolean algebras are considered.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A *tautology* is a propositional formula that is assigned truth value *1* by every truth assignment of its propositional variables to an arbitrary Boolean algebra (or, equivalently, every truth assignment to the two element Boolean algebra).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] These semantics permit a translation between tautologies of propositional logic and equational theorems of Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Every tautology Φ of propositional logic can be expressed as the Boolean equation Φ = 1, which will be a theorem of Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Conversely, every theorem Φ = Ψ of Boolean algebra corresponds to the tautologies (Φ ∨ ¬Ψ) ∧ (¬Φ ∨ Ψ) and (Φ ∧ Ψ) ∨ (¬Φ ∧ ¬Ψ).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] If → is in the language, these last tautologies can also be written as (Φ → Ψ) ∧ (Ψ → Φ), or as two separate theorems Φ → Ψ and Ψ → Φ; if ≡ is available, then the single tautology Φ ≡ Ψ can be used.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] One motivating application of propositional calculus is the analysis of propositions and deductive arguments in natural language.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Replacing *P* by *x* = 3 or any other proposition is called *instantiation* of *P* by that proposition.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The result of instantiating *P* in an abstract proposition is called an *instance* of the proposition.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Thus, *x* = 3 → *x* = 3 is a tautology by virtue of being an instance of the abstract tautology *P* → *P*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] All occurrences of the instantiated variable must be instantiated with the same proposition, to avoid such nonsense as *P* → *x* = 3 or *x* = 3 → *x* = 4.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Propositional calculus restricts attention to abstract propositions, those built up from propositional variables using Boolean operations.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Instantiation is still possible within propositional calculus, but only by instantiating propositional variables by abstract propositions, such as instantiating *Q* by *Q* → *P* in *P* → (*Q* → *P*) to yield the instance *P* → ((*Q* → *P*) → *P*).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] (The availability of instantiation as part of the machinery of propositional calculus avoids the need for metavariables within the language of propositional calculus, since ordinary propositional variables can be considered within the language to denote arbitrary propositions.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] An axiomatization of propositional calculus is a set of tautologies called *axioms* and one or more inference rules for producing new tautologies from old.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] A *proof* in an axiom system *A* is a finite nonempty sequence of propositions each of which is either an instance of an axiom of *A* or follows by some rule of *A* from propositions appearing earlier in the proof (thereby disallowing circular reasoning).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The last proposition is the *theorem* proved by the proof.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Every nonempty initial segment of a proof is itself a proof, whence every proposition in a proof is itself a theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] An axiomatization is *sound* when every theorem is a tautology, and *complete* when every tautology is a theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Propositional calculus is commonly organized as a Hilbert system, whose operations are just those of Boolean algebra and whose theorems are Boolean tautologies, those Boolean terms equal to the Boolean constant 1.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Another form is sequent calculus, which has two sorts, propositions as in ordinary propositional calculus, and pairs of lists of propositions called *sequents*, such as *A* ∨ *B*, *A* ∧ *C*, ... ⊢ *A*, *B* → *C*, ....
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The two halves of a sequent are called the antecedent and the succedent respectively.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The customary metavariable denoting an antecedent or part thereof is Γ, and for a succedent Δ; thus Γ, *A* ⊢ Δ would denote a sequent whose succedent is a list Δ and whose antecedent is a list Γ with an additional proposition *A* appended after it.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The antecedent is interpreted as the conjunction of its propositions, the succedent as the disjunction of its propositions, and the sequent itself as the entailment of the succedent by the antecedent.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] Entailment differs from implication in that whereas the latter is a binary *operation* that returns a value in a Boolean algebra, the former is a binary *relation* which either holds or does not hold.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] In this sense, entailment is an *external* form of implication, meaning external to the Boolean algebra, thinking of the reader of the sequent as also being external and interpreting and comparing antecedents and succedents in some Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] The natural interpretation of ⊢ is as ≤ in the partial order of the Boolean algebra defined by *x* ≤ *y* just when *x* ∨ *y* = *y*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p01] This ability to mix external implication ⊢ and internal implication → in the one logic is among the essential differences between sequent calculus and propositional calculus.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Boolean algebra as the calculus of two values is fundamental to computer circuits, computer programming, and mathematical logic, and is also used in other areas of mathematics such as set theory and statistics.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] In the early 20th century, several electrical engineers intuitively recognized that Boolean algebra was analogous to the behavior of certain types of electrical circuits.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Claude Shannon formally proved such behavior was logically equivalent to Boolean algebra in his 1937 master's thesis, *A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Today, all modern general-purpose computers perform their functions using two-value Boolean logic; that is, their electrical circuits are a physical manifestation of two-value Boolean logic.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] They achieve this in various ways: as voltages on wires in high-speed circuits and capacitive storage devices, as orientations of a magnetic domain in ferromagnetic storage devices, as holes in punched cards or paper tape, and so on.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Of course, it is possible to code more than two symbols in any given medium.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] For example, one might use respectively 0, 1, 2, and 3 volts to code a four-symbol alphabet on a wire, or holes of different sizes in a punched card.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] In practice, the tight constraints of high speed, small size, and low power combine to make noise a major factor.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] This makes it hard to distinguish between symbols when there are several possible symbols that could occur at a single site.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Rather than attempting to distinguish between four voltages on one wire, digital designers have settled on two voltages per wire, high and low.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Computers use two-value Boolean circuits for the above reasons.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] The most common computer architectures use ordered sequences of Boolean values, called bits, of 32 or 64 values, e.g.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] When programming in machine code, assembly language, and certain other programming languages, programmers work with the low-level digital structure of the data registers.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] These registers operate on voltages, where zero volts represents Boolean 0, and a reference voltage (often +5 V, +3.3 V, or +1.8 V) represents Boolean 1.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Such languages support both numeric operations and logical operations.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] In this context, "numeric" means that the computer treats sequences of bits as binary numbers (base two numbers) and executes arithmetic operations like add, subtract, multiply, or divide.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] "Logical" refers to the Boolean logical operations of disjunction, conjunction, and negation between two sequences of bits, in which each bit in one sequence is simply compared to its counterpart in the other sequence.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Programmers therefore have the option of working in and applying the rules of either numeric algebra or Boolean algebra as needed.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] A core differentiating feature between these families of operations is the existence of the carry operation in the first but not the second.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Other areas where two values is a good choice are the law and mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] In everyday relaxed conversation, nuanced or complex answers such as "maybe" or "only on the weekend" are acceptable.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] In more focused situations such as a court of law or theorem-based mathematics, however, it is deemed advantageous to frame questions so as to admit a simple yes-or-no answer—is the defendant guilty or not guilty, is the proposition true or false—and to disallow any other answer.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] However limiting this might prove in practice for the respondent, the principle of the simple yes–no question has become a central feature of both judicial and mathematical logic, making two-valued logic deserving of organization and study in its own right.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] A central concept of set theory is membership.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] An organization may permit multiple degrees of membership, such as novice, associate, and full.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] With sets, however, an element is either in or out.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] The candidates for membership in a set work just like the wires in a digital computer: each candidate is either a member or a nonmember, just as each wire is either high or low.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Algebra being a fundamental tool in any area amenable to mathematical treatment, these considerations combine to make the algebra of two values of fundamental importance to computer hardware, mathematical logic, and set theory.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Two-valued logic can be extended to multi-valued logic, notably by replacing the Boolean domain {0, 1} with the unit interval [0,1], in which case rather than only taking values 0 or 1, any value between and including 0 and 1 can be assumed.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Algebraically, negation (NOT) is replaced with 1 − *x*, conjunction (AND) is replaced with multiplication (*xy*), and disjunction (OR) is defined via De Morgan's law.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Interpreting these values as logical truth values yields a multi-valued logic, which forms the basis for fuzzy logic and probabilistic logic.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] In these interpretations, a value is interpreted as the "degree" of truth – to what extent a proposition is true, or the probability that the proposition is true.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] The original application for Boolean operations was mathematical logic, where it combines the truth values, true or false, of individual formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Natural languages such as English have words for several Boolean operations, in particular conjunction (*and*), disjunction (*or*), negation (*not*), and implication (*implies*).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] When used to combine situational assertions such as "the block is on the table" and "cats drink milk", which naïvely are either true or false, the meanings of these logical connectives often have the meaning of their logical counterparts.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Questions can be similar: the order "Is the sky blue, and why is the sky blue?" makes more sense than the reverse order.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Conjunctive commands about behavior are like behavioral assertions, as in *get dressed and go to school*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Disjunctive commands such *love me or leave me* or *fish or cut bait* tend to be asymmetric via the implication that one alternative is less preferable.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Conjoined nouns such as *tea and milk* generally describe aggregation as with set union while *tea or milk* is a choice.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] However, context can reverse these senses, as in *your choices are coffee and tea* which usually means the same as *your choices are coffee or tea* (alternatives).
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Double negation, as in "I don't not like milk", rarely means literally "I do like milk" but rather conveys some sort of hedging, as though to imply that there is a third possibility.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] "Not not P" can be loosely interpreted as "surely P", and although *P* necessarily implies "not not *P*," the converse is suspect in English, much as with intuitionistic logic.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] In view of the highly idiosyncratic usage of conjunctions in natural languages, Boolean algebra cannot be considered a reliable framework for interpreting them.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Boolean operations are used in digital logic to combine the bits carried on individual wires, thereby interpreting them over {0,1}.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] When a vector of *n* identical binary gates are used to combine two bit vectors each of *n* bits, the individual bit operations can be understood collectively as a single operation on values from a Boolean algebra with 2*n* elements.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Naive set theory interprets Boolean operations as acting on subsets of a given set *X*.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] As we saw earlier this behavior exactly parallels the coordinate-wise combinations of bit vectors, with the union of two sets corresponding to the disjunction of two bit vectors and so on.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Modern video cards offer all 223 = 256 ternary operations for this purpose, with the choice of operation being a one-byte (8-bit) parameter.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] At run time the video card interprets the byte as the raster operation indicated by the original expression in a uniform way that requires remarkably little hardware and which takes time completely independent of the complexity of the expression.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Solid modeling systems for computer aided design offer a variety of methods for building objects from other objects, combination by Boolean operations being one of them.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] In this method the space in which objects exist is understood as a set *S* of voxels (the three-dimensional analogue of pixels in two-dimensional graphics) and shapes are defined as subsets of *S*, allowing objects to be combined as sets via union, intersection, etc.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] One obvious use is in building a complex shape from simple shapes simply as the union of the latter.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Thus given two shapes one to be machined and the other the material to be removed, the result of machining the former to remove the latter is described simply as their set difference.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] Search engine queries also employ Boolean logic.
[src:logic-foundations/boolean-algebra-p02] For this application, each web page on the Internet may be considered to be an "element" of a "set." The following examples use a syntax supported by Google.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] In propositional logic and Boolean algebra, **De Morgan's laws**, also known as **De Morgan's theorem**, are a pair of transformation rules that are both valid rules of inference.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] They are named after Augustus De Morgan, a 19th-century British mathematician.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The rules allow the expression of conjunctions and disjunctions purely in terms of each other via negation.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] where "A or B" is an "inclusive or" meaning *at least* one of A or B rather than an "exclusive or" that means *exactly* one of A or B.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Another form of De Morgan's law is the following as seen below.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Applications of the rules include simplification of logical expressions in computer programs and digital circuit designs.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] De Morgan's laws are an example of a more general concept of mathematical duality.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] where P and Q are propositions expressed in some formal system.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The **generalized De Morgan's laws** provide an equivalence for negating a conjunction or disjunction involving multiple terms.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] These laws generalize De Morgan's original laws for negating conjunctions and disjunctions.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] De Morgan's laws are normally shown in the compact form above, with the negation of the output on the left and negation of the inputs on the right.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] This emphasizes the need to invert both the inputs and the output, as well as change the operator when doing a substitution.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] where *I* is some, possibly countably or uncountably infinite, indexing set.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] In set notation, De Morgan's laws can be remembered using the mnemonic "break the line, change the sign".
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] De Morgan's laws commonly apply to text searching using Boolean operators AND, OR, and NOT.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Consider a set of documents containing the words "cats" and "dogs".
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Document 1: Contains only the word "cats".
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Document 3: Contains both "cats" and "dogs".
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Document 4: Contains neither "cats" nor "dogs".
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] To evaluate Search A, clearly the search "(cats OR dogs)" will hit on Documents 1, 2, and 3.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] So the negation of that search (which is Search A) will hit everything else, which is Document 4.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Evaluating Search B, the search "(NOT cats)" will hit on documents that do not contain "cats", which is Documents 2 and 4.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Similarly the search "(NOT dogs)" will hit on Documents 1 and 4.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Applying the AND operator to these two searches (which is Search B) will hit on the documents that are common to these two searches, which is Document 4.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Here is a more concrete example to illustrate how De Morgan's laws operate in practice.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Let's consider the statement: "It is not the case that a number is both even and positive".
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] This transformation demonstrates how negation is distrubuted across a conjuction by negating each component and switching the logical operator.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Step-by-step rewrites such as this are especially useful when simplifying logical expressions in proofs and problem solving.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The laws are named after Augustus De Morgan (1806–1871), who introduced a formal version of the laws to classical propositional logic.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The first explicit statement of De Morgan’s laws in his own work can be found in his 1847 book *Formal Logic*.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] De Morgan's formulation was influenced by the algebraization of logic undertaken by George Boole, which later cemented De Morgan's claim to the find.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Nevertheless, a similar observation was made by Aristotle, and was known to Greek and Medieval logicians.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] For example, in the 14th century, William of Ockham wrote down the words that would result by reading the laws out.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Jean Buridan, in his *Summulae de Dialectica*, also describes rules of conversion that follow the lines of De Morgan's laws.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Still, De Morgan is given credit for stating the laws in the terms of modern formal logic, and incorporating them into the language of logic.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] De Morgan's laws can be proved easily, and may even seem trivial.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Nonetheless, these laws are helpful in making valid inferences in proofs and deductive arguments.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] De Morgan's theorem may be applied to the negation of a disjunction or the negation of a conjunction in all or part of a formula.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] If either A or B *were* true, then the disjunction of A and B would be true, making its negation false.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Presented in English, this follows the logic that "since two things are both false, it is also false that either of them is true".
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Working in the opposite direction, the second expression asserts that A is false and B is false (or equivalently that "not A" and "not B" are true).
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Knowing this, a disjunction of A and B must be false also.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The negation of said disjunction must thus be true, and the result is identical to the first claim.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The application of De Morgan's theorem to conjunction is very similar to its application to a disjunction both in form and rationale.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] In order for this claim to be true, either or both of A or B must be false, for if they both were true, then the conjunction of A and B would be true, making its negation false.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Thus, one (at least) or more of A and B must be false (or equivalently, one or more of "not A" and "not B" must be true).
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Presented in a natural language like English, it is expressed as "since it is false that two things are both true, at least one of them must be false".
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Working in the opposite direction again, the second expression asserts that at least one of "not A" and "not B" must be true, or equivalently that at least one of A and B must be false.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Since at least one of them must be false, then their conjunction would likewise be false.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Negating said conjunction thus results in a true expression, and this expression is identical to the first claim.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Here we use ${\overline {A}}$ to denote the complement of A, as above in § Set theory and Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The proof that ${\overline {A\cap B}}={\overline {A}}\cup {\overline {B}}$ is completed in 2 steps by proving both ${\overline {A\cap B}}\subseteq {\overline {A}}\cup {\overline {B}}$ and ${\overline {A}}\cup {\overline {B}}\subseteq {\overline {A\cap B}}$ .
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Because $A\cap B=\{\,y\ |\ y\in A\wedge y\in B\,\}$ , it must be the case that $x\not \in A$ or $x\not \in B$ .
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] that is, ${\overline {A\cap B}}\subseteq {\overline {A}}\cup {\overline {B}}$ .
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] To prove the reverse direction, let $x\in {\overline {A}}\cup {\overline {B}}$ , and for contradiction assume $x\not \in {\overline {A\cap B}}$ .
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] so it follows that $x\in A$ and $x\in B$ , and thus $x\not \in {\overline {A}}$ and $x\not \in {\overline {B}}$ .
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] therefore, the assumption $x\not \in {\overline {A\cap B}}$ must not be the case, meaning that $x\in {\overline {A\cap B}}$ .
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] that is, ${\overline {A}}\cup {\overline {B}}\subseteq {\overline {A\cap B}}$ .
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] If ${\overline {A}}\cup {\overline {B}}\subseteq {\overline {A\cap B}}$ *and* ${\overline {A\cap B}}\subseteq {\overline {A}}\cup {\overline {B}}$ , then ${\overline {A\cap B}}={\overline {A}}\cup {\overline {B}}$ ; this concludes the proof of De Morgan's law.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The other De Morgan's law, ${\overline {A\cup B}}={\overline {A}}\cap {\overline {B}}$ , is proven similarly.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] In extensions of classical propositional logic, the duality still holds (that is, to any logical operator one can always find its dual), since in the presence of the identities governing negation, one may always introduce an operator that is the De Morgan dual of another.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] This leads to an important property of logics based on classical logic, namely the existence of negation normal forms: any formula is equivalent to another formula where negations only occur applied to the non-logical atoms of the formula.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The existence of negation normal forms drives many applications, for example in digital circuit design, where it is used to manipulate the types of logic gates, and in formal logic, where it is needed to find the conjunctive normal form and disjunctive normal form of a formula.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Computer programmers use them to simplify or properly negate complicated logical conditions.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] They are also often useful in computations in elementary probability theory.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] verifying the quantifier dualities in the model.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] In its application to the alethic modalities of possibility and necessity, Aristotle observed this case, and in the case of normal modal logic, the relationship of these modal operators to the quantification can be understood by setting up models using Kripke semantics.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Three out of the four implications of de Morgan's laws hold in intuitionistic logic.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The converse of the last implication does not hold in pure intuitionistic logic.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] That is, the failure of the joint proposition $P\land Q$ cannot necessarily be resolved to the failure of either of the two conjuncts.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] For example, from knowing it not to be the case that both Alice and Bob showed up to their date, it does not follow who did not show up.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] This weak form can be used as a foundation for an intermediate logic.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] For a refined version of the failing law concerning existential statements, see the lesser limited principle of omniscience ${\mathrm {LLPO} }$ , which however is different from ${\mathrm {WLPO} }$ .
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] The validity of the other three De Morgan's laws remains true if negation $\neg P$ is replaced by implication $P\to C$ for some arbitrary constant predicate C, meaning that the above laws are still true in minimal logic.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] are tautologies even in minimal logic with negation replaced with implying a fixed Q , while the converse of the last law does not have to be true in general.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] but their inversion implies excluded middle, ${\mathrm {PEM} }$ .
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] De Morgan's laws are commonly cited in digital circuit design and Boolean algebra, however, they also play an important role in reasoning and computation.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] De Morgan's laws are utilized in probability theory, allowing one to simplify complements of compound events.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Expressions involving "not both" or "not either" can be rewritten in more manageable forms.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] In computer science, these laws are frequestly applied when rewriting conditional statements.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] Negating a compound condition in code often requires transforming an AND condition into an OR condition with negated components, illustrating how these laws improve both readabillity and correctness when designing algorithms.
[src:logic-foundations/de-morgan-s-laws] De Morgan's laws are also useful in formal proofs. where transforming logical statements into equivalent forms can make arguments earier to construct and verify.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] "Theory" is sometimes understood in a more formal sense as just a set of sentences in first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The term "first-order" distinguishes first-order logic from higher-order logic, in which there are predicates having predicates or functions as arguments, or in which quantification over predicates, functions, or both, are permitted.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In first-order theories, predicates are often associated with sets.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In interpreted higher-order theories, predicates may be interpreted as sets of sets.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There are many deductive systems for first-order logic which are both sound, i.e. all provable statements are true in all models; and complete, i.e. all statements which are true in all models are provable.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Although the logical consequence relation is only semidecidable, much progress has been made in automated theorem proving in first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] First-order logic also satisfies several metalogical theorems that make it amenable to analysis in proof theory, such as the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem and the compactness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] First-order logic is the standard for the formalization of mathematics into axioms, and is studied in the foundations of mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Peano arithmetic and Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory are axiomatizations of number theory and set theory, respectively, into first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] No first-order theory, however, has the strength to uniquely describe a structure with an infinite domain, such as the natural numbers or the real line.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Axiom systems that do fully describe these two structures, i.e. categorical axiom systems, can be obtained in stronger logics such as second-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Historically speaking, the foundations of first-order logic were developed independently by Gottlob Frege and Charles Sanders Peirce in the 1880s.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] However, the distinction between first-order and higher-order logic was not well understood until metalogical ideas and results arrived, such as Gödel's completeness theorem in 1929.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] By the 1940s, first-order logic had become the dominant language of mathematical foundations.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] While propositional logic deals with simple declarative propositions, first-order logic additionally covers predicates and quantification.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A predicate evaluates to true or false for an entity or entities in the domain of discourse.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Consider the two sentences "Socrates is a philosopher" and "Plato is a philosopher".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In propositional logic, these sentences themselves are viewed as the individuals of study, and might be denoted, for example, by variables such as *p* and *q*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] They are not viewed as an application of a predicate, such as ${\text{isPhilosopher}}$ , to any particular objects in the domain of discourse, instead viewing them as purely an utterance which is either true or false.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] However, in first-order logic, these two sentences may be framed as statements that a certain individual or non-logical object has a property.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In this example, both sentences happen to have the common form ${\text{isPhilosopher}}(x)$ for some individual x , in the first sentence the value of the variable *x* is "Socrates", and in the second sentence it is "Plato".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Due to the ability to speak about non-logical individuals along with the original logical connectives, first-order logic includes propositional logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The truth of a formula such as "*x* is a philosopher" depends on which object is denoted by *x* and on the interpretation of the predicate "is a philosopher".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Consequently, "*x* is a philosopher" alone does not have a definite truth value of true or false, and is akin to a sentence fragment.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Relationships between predicates can be stated using logical connectives.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, the first-order formula "if *x* is a philosopher, then *x* is a scholar", is a conditional statement with "*x* is a philosopher" as its hypothesis, and "*x* is a scholar" as its conclusion, which again needs specification of *x* in order to have a definite truth value.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Quantifiers can be applied to variables in a formula.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The variable *x* in the previous formula can be universally quantified, for instance, with the first-order sentence "For every *x*, if *x* is a philosopher, then *x* is a scholar".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The universal quantifier "for every" in this sentence expresses the idea that the claim "if *x* is a philosopher, then *x* is a scholar" holds for *all* choices of *x*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The *negation* of the sentence "For every *x*, if *x* is a philosopher, then *x* is a scholar" is logically equivalent to the sentence "There exists *x* such that *x* is a philosopher and *x* is not a scholar".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The existential quantifier "there exists" expresses the idea that the claim "*x* is a philosopher and *x* is not a scholar" holds for *some* choice of *x*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The predicates "is a philosopher" and "is a scholar" each take a single variable.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In general, predicates can take several variables.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In the first-order sentence "Socrates is the teacher of Plato", the predicate "is the teacher of" takes two variables.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] An interpretation (or model) of a first-order formula specifies what each predicate means, and the entities that can instantiate the variables.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These entities form the domain of discourse or universe, which is usually required to be a nonempty set.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There are two key parts of first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The syntax determines which finite sequences of symbols are well-formed expressions in first-order logic, while the semantics determines the meanings behind these expressions.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Unlike natural languages, such as English, the language of first-order logic is completely formal, so that it can be mechanically determined whether a given expression is well formed.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There are two key types of well-formed expressions: *terms*, which intuitively represent objects, and *formulas*, which intuitively express statements that can be true or false.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The terms and formulas of first-order logic are strings of *symbols*, where all the symbols together form the *alphabet* of the language.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] As with all formal languages, the nature of the symbols themselves is outside the scope of formal logic; they are often regarded simply as letters and punctuation symbols.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] It is common to divide the symbols of the alphabet into *logical symbols*, which always have the same meaning, and *non-logical symbols*, whose meaning varies by interpretation.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, the logical symbol $\land$ always represents "and"; it is never interpreted as "or", which is represented by the logical symbol $\lor$ .
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] However, a non-logical predicate symbol such as Phil(*x*) could be interpreted to mean "*x* is a philosopher", "*x* is a man named Philip", or any other unary predicate depending on the interpretation at hand.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Not all of these symbols are required in first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Either one of the quantifiers along with negation, conjunction (or disjunction), variables, brackets, and equality suffices.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Non-logical symbols represent predicates (relations), functions and constants.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] When the arity of a predicate symbol or function symbol is clear from context, the superscript *n* is often omitted.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In this traditional approach, there is only one language of first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] This approach is still common, especially in philosophically oriented books.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A more recent practice is to use different non-logical symbols according to the application one has in mind.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Therefore, it has become necessary to name the set of all non-logical symbols used in a particular application.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Typical signatures in mathematics are {1, ×} or just {×} for groups, or {0, 1, +, ×, <} for ordered fields.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There are no restrictions on the number of non-logical symbols.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The signature can be empty, finite, or infinite, even uncountable.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Uncountable signatures occur for example in modern proofs of the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Though signatures might in some cases imply how non-logical symbols are to be interpreted, interpretation of the non-logical symbols in the signature is separate (and not necessarily fixed).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Signatures concern syntax rather than semantics.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The traditional approach can be recovered in the modern approach, by simply specifying the "custom" signature to consist of the traditional sequences of non-logical symbols.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The formation rules define the terms and formulas of first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] When terms and formulas are represented as strings of symbols, these rules can be used to write a formal grammar for terms and formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These rules are generally context-free (each production has a single symbol on the left side), except that the set of symbols may be allowed to be infinite and there may be many start symbols, for example the variables in the case of terms.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In particular, symbols denoting individual constants are nullary function symbols, and thus are terms.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Only expressions which can be obtained by finitely many applications of rules 1 and 2 are terms.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, no expression involving a predicate symbol is a term.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] If $\varphi$ is a formula, then $\lnot \varphi$ is a formula.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] If ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\psi$ ⁠ are formulas, then ( $\varphi \rightarrow \psi$ ) is a formula.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Similar rules apply to other binary logical connectives.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] If $\varphi$ is a formula and *x* is a variable, then $\forall x\varphi$ (for all x, $\varphi$ holds) and $\exists x\varphi$ (there exists x such that $\varphi$ ) are formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Only expressions which can be obtained by finitely many applications of rules 1–4 are formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The formulas obtained from the first rule are said to be *atomic formulas*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] is a formula, if *f* is a unary function symbol, *P* a unary predicate symbol, and Q a ternary predicate symbol.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] However, $\forall x\,x\rightarrow$ is not a formula, although it is a string of symbols from the alphabet.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The role of the parentheses in the definition is to ensure that any formula can only be obtained in one way—by following the inductive definition (i.e., there is a unique parse tree for each formula).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] This property is known as *unique readability* of formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There are many conventions for where parentheses are used in formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, some authors use colons or full stops instead of parentheses, or change the places in which parentheses are inserted.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Each author's particular definition must be accompanied by a proof of unique readability.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For convenience, conventions have been developed about the precedence of the logical operators, to avoid the need to write parentheses in some cases.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These rules are similar to the order of operations in arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Moreover, extra punctuation not required by the definition may be inserted—to make formulas easier to read.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In a formula, a variable may occur *free* or *bound* (or both).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] One formalization of this notion is due to Quine, first the concept of a variable occurrence is defined, then whether a variable occurrence is free or bound, then whether a variable symbol overall is free or bound.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In order to distinguish different occurrences of the identical symbol *x*, each occurrence of a variable symbol *x* in a formula φ is identified with the initial substring of φ up to the point at which said instance of the symbol *x* appears.p.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] 297 Then, an occurrence of *x* is said to be bound if that occurrence of *x* lies within the scope of at least one of either $\exists x$ or $\forall x$ .
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Finally, *x* is bound in φ if all occurrences of *x* in φ are bound.pp.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Intuitively, a variable symbol is free in a formula if at no point is it quantified:pp.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] 142–143 in ∀*y* *P*(*x*, *y*), the sole occurrence of variable *x* is free while that of *y* is bound.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The free and bound variable occurrences in a formula are defined inductively as follows.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Moreover, there are no bound variables in any atomic formula.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The same rule applies to any other binary connective in place of →.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, in ∀*x* ∀*y* (*P*(*x*) → *Q*(*x*,*f*(*x*),*z*)), *x* and *y* occur only bound, *z* occurs only free, and *w* is neither because it does not occur in the formula.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Free and bound variables of a formula need not be disjoint sets: in the formula *P*(*x*) → ∀*x* *Q*(*x*), the first occurrence of *x*, as argument of *P*, is free while the second one, as argument of *Q*, is bound.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A formula in first-order logic with no free variable occurrences is called a *first-order sentence*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These are the formulas that will have well-defined truth values under an interpretation.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, whether a formula such as Phil(*x*) is true must depend on what *x* represents.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] But the sentence ∃*x* Phil(*x*) will be either true or false in a given interpretation.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In mathematics, the language of ordered abelian groups has one constant symbol 0, one unary function symbol −, one binary function symbol +, and one binary relation symbol ≤.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The axioms for ordered abelian groups can be expressed as a set of sentences in the language.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] An interpretation of a first-order language assigns a denotation to each non-logical symbol (predicate symbol, function symbol, or constant symbol) in that language.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] It also determines a domain of discourse that specifies the range of the quantifiers.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The result is that each term is assigned an object that it represents, each predicate is assigned a property of objects, and each sentence is assigned a truth value.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In this way, an interpretation provides semantic meaning to the terms, predicates, and formulas of the language.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The study of the interpretations of formal languages is called formal semantics.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] What follows is a description of the standard or Tarskian semantics for first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The most common way of specifying an interpretation (especially in mathematics) is to specify a *structure* (also called a *model*; see below).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The structure consists of a domain of discourse *D* and an interpretation function I mapping non-logical symbols to predicates, functions, and constants.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The domain of discourse *D* is a nonempty set of "objects" of some kind.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, one can take *D* to be the set of integers.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A formula evaluates to true or false given an interpretation and a **variable assignment** μ that associates an element of the domain of discourse with each variable.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The reason that a variable assignment is required is to give meanings to formulas with free variables, such as $y=x$ .
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The truth value of this formula changes depending on the values that *x* and *y* denote.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] First, the variable assignment μ can be extended to all terms of the language, with the result that each term maps to a single element of the domain of discourse.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Next, each formula is assigned a truth value.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The inductive definition used to make this assignment is called the T-schema.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] If a formula does not contain free variables, and thus is a sentence, then the initial variable assignment does not affect its truth value.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In other words, a sentence is true according to *M* and $\mu$ if and only if it is true according to *M* and every other variable assignment $\mu '$ .
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There is a second common approach to defining truth values that does not rely on variable assignment functions.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Instead, given an interpretation *M*, one first adds to the signature a collection of constant symbols, one for each element of the domain of discourse in *M*; say that for each *d* in the domain the constant symbol *c**d* is fixed.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The interpretation is extended so that each new constant symbol is assigned to its corresponding element of the domain.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] This alternate approach gives exactly the same truth values to all sentences as the approach via variable assignments.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] If a sentence φ evaluates to *true* under a given interpretation *M*, one says that *M* *satisfies* φ; this is denoted $M\vDash \varphi$ .
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A sentence is *satisfiable* if there is some interpretation under which it is true.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] This is a bit different from the symbol $\vDash$ from model theory, where $M\vDash \phi$ denotes satisfiability in a model, i.e.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] "there is a suitable assignment of values in M 's domain to variable symbols of $\phi$ ".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Satisfiability of formulas with free variables is more complicated, because an interpretation on its own does not determine the truth value of such a formula.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The most common convention is that a formula φ with free variables $x_{1}$ , ..., $x_{n}$ is said to be satisfied by an interpretation if the formula φ remains true regardless which individuals from the domain of discourse are assigned to its free variables $x_{1}$ , ..., $x_{n}$ .
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] This has the same effect as saying that a formula φ is satisfied if and only if its universal closure $\forall x_{1}\dots \forall x_{n}\phi (x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ is satisfied.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A formula is *logically valid* (or simply *valid*) if it is true in every interpretation.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These formulas play a role similar to tautologies in propositional logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A formula φ is a *logical consequence* of a formula ψ if every interpretation that makes ψ true also makes φ true.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In this case one says that φ is logically implied by ψ.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] An alternate approach to the semantics of first-order logic proceeds via abstract algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] This approach generalizes the Lindenbaum–Tarski algebras of propositional logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These algebras are all lattices that properly extend the two-element Boolean algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Tarski and Givant (1987) showed that the fragment of first-order logic that has no atomic sentence lying in the scope of more than three quantifiers has the same expressive power as relation algebra.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] This fragment is of great interest because it suffices for Peano arithmetic and most axiomatic set theory, including the canonical Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (ZFC).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] They also prove that first-order logic with a primitive ordered pair is equivalent to a relation algebra with two ordered pair projection functions.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A *first-order theory* of a particular signature is a set of axioms, which are sentences consisting of symbols from that signature.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The set of axioms is often finite or recursively enumerable, in which case the theory is called *effective*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Some authors require theories to also include all logical consequences of the axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The axioms are considered to hold within the theory and from them other sentences that hold within the theory can be derived.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A first-order structure that satisfies all sentences in a given theory is said to be a *model* of the theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] An *elementary class* is the set of all structures satisfying a particular theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These classes are a main subject of study in model theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Many theories have an *intended interpretation*, a certain model that is kept in mind when studying the theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, the intended interpretation of Peano arithmetic consists of the usual natural numbers with their usual operations.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] However, the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem shows that most first-order theories will also have other, nonstandard models.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A theory is *consistent* (within a deductive system) if it is not possible to prove a contradiction from the axioms of the theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A theory is *complete* if, for every formula in its signature, either that formula or its negation is a logical consequence of the axioms of the theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Gödel's incompleteness theorem shows that effective first-order theories that include a sufficient portion of the arithmetic of the natural numbers can never be both consistent and complete.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The definition above requires that the domain of discourse of any interpretation must be nonempty.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There are settings, such as inclusive logic, where empty domains are permitted.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Moreover, if a class of algebraic structures includes an empty structure (for example, there is an empty poset), that class can only be an elementary class in first-order logic if empty domains are permitted or the empty structure is removed from the class.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Thus, when the empty domain is permitted, it must often be treated as a special case.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Most authors, however, simply exclude the empty domain by definition.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A *deductive system* is used to demonstrate, on a purely syntactic basis, that one formula is a logical consequence of another formula.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There are many such systems for first-order logic, including Hilbert-style deductive systems, natural deduction, the sequent calculus, the tableaux method, and resolution.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These share the common property that a deduction is a finite syntactic object; the format of this object, and the way it is constructed, vary widely.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These finite deductions themselves are often called *derivations* in proof theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] They are also often called *proofs* but are completely formalized unlike natural-language mathematical proofs.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A deductive system is *sound* if any formula that can be derived in the system is logically valid.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Conversely, a deductive system is *complete* if every logically valid formula is derivable.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] All of the systems discussed in this article are both sound and complete.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] They also share the property that it is possible to effectively verify that a purportedly valid deduction is actually a deduction; such deduction systems are called *effective*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A key property of deductive systems is that they are purely syntactic, so that derivations can be verified without considering any interpretation.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Thus, a sound argument is correct in every possible interpretation of the language, regardless of whether that interpretation is about mathematics, economics, or some other area.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In general, logical consequence in first-order logic is only semidecidable: if a sentence A logically implies a sentence B then this can be discovered (for example, by searching for a proof until one is found, using some effective, sound, complete proof system).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] However, if A does not logically imply B, this does not mean that A logically implies the negation of B.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There is no effective procedure that, given formulas A and B, always correctly decides whether A logically implies B.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A *rule of inference* states that, given a particular formula (or set of formulas) with a certain property as a hypothesis, another specific formula (or set of formulas) can be derived as a conclusion.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The rule is sound (or truth-preserving) if it preserves validity in the sense that whenever any interpretation satisfies the hypothesis, that interpretation also satisfies the conclusion.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, one common rule of inference is the *rule of substitution*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] If *t* is a term and φ is a formula possibly containing the variable *x*, then φ[*t*/*x*] is the result of replacing all free instances of *x* by *t* in φ.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The substitution rule states that for any φ and any term *t*, one can conclude φ[*t*/*x*] from φ provided that no free variable of *t* becomes bound during the substitution process.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] To see why the restriction on bound variables is necessary, consider the logically valid formula φ given by $\exists x(x=y)$ , in the signature of (0,1,+,×,=) of arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] If *t* is the term "x + 1", the formula φ[*t*/*y*] is $\exists x(x=x+1)$ , which will be false in many interpretations.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The problem is that the free variable *x* of *t* became bound during the substitution.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The intended replacement can be obtained by renaming the bound variable *x* of φ to something else, say *z*, so that the formula after substitution is $\exists z(z=x+1)$ , which is again logically valid.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The substitution rule demonstrates several common aspects of rules of inference.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] It is entirely syntactical; one can tell whether it was correctly applied without appeal to any interpretation.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] It has (syntactically defined) limitations on when it can be applied, which must be respected to preserve the correctness of derivations.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Moreover, as is often the case, these limitations are necessary because of interactions between free and bound variables that occur during syntactic manipulations of the formulas involved in the inference rule.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] A deduction in a Hilbert-style deductive system is a list of formulas, each of which is a *logical axiom*, a hypothesis that has been assumed for the derivation at hand or follows from previous formulas via a rule of inference.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The logical axioms consist of several axiom schemas of logically valid formulas; these encompass a significant amount of propositional logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The rules of inference enable the manipulation of quantifiers.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Typical Hilbert-style systems have a small number of rules of inference, along with several infinite schemas of logical axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] It is common to have only modus ponens and universal generalization as rules of inference.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Natural deduction systems resemble Hilbert-style systems in that a deduction is a finite list of formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] However, natural deduction systems have no logical axioms; they compensate by adding additional rules of inference that can be used to manipulate the logical connectives in formulas in the proof.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The sequent calculus was developed to study the properties of natural deduction systems.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] where A1, ..., A*n*, B1, ..., B*k* are formulas and the turnstile symbol $\vdash$ is used as punctuation to separate the two halves.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Intuitively, a sequent expresses the idea that $(A_{1}\land \cdots \land A_{n})$ implies $(B_{1}\lor \cdots \lor B_{k})$ .
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Unlike the methods just described the derivations in the tableaux method are not lists of formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Instead, a derivation is a tree of formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] To show that a formula A is provable, the tableaux method attempts to demonstrate that the negation of A is unsatisfiable.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The tree of the derivation has $\lnot A$ at its root; the tree branches in a way that reflects the structure of the formula.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, to show that $C\lor D$ is unsatisfiable requires showing that C and D are each unsatisfiable; this corresponds to a branching point in the tree with parent $C\lor D$ and children C and D.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The resolution rule is a single rule of inference that, together with unification, is sound and complete for first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] As with the tableaux method, a formula is proved by showing that the negation of the formula is unsatisfiable.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Resolution is commonly used in automated theorem proving.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The resolution method works only with formulas that are disjunctions of atomic formulas; arbitrary formulas must first be converted to this form through Skolemization.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The resolution rule states that from the hypotheses $A_{1}\lor \cdots \lor A_{k}\lor C$ and $B_{1}\lor \cdots \lor B_{l}\lor \lnot C$ , the conclusion $A_{1}\lor \cdots \lor A_{k}\lor B_{1}\lor \cdots \lor B_{l}$ can be obtained.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] Many identities can be proved, which establish equivalences between particular formulas.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These identities allow for rearranging formulas by moving quantifiers across other connectives and are useful for putting formulas in prenex normal form.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] There are several different conventions for using equality (or identity) in first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The most common convention, known as **first-order logic with equality**, includes the equality symbol as a primitive logical symbol which is always interpreted as the real equality relation between members of the domain of discourse, such that the "two" given members are the same member.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] This approach also adds certain axioms about equality to the deductive system employed.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] These are axiom schemas, each of which specifies an infinite set of axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The third schema is known as *Leibniz's law*, "the principle of substitutivity", "the indiscernibility of identicals", or "the replacement property".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] An alternate approach considers the equality relation to be a non-logical symbol.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] This convention is known as *first-order logic without equality*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] If an equality relation is included in the signature, the axioms of equality must now be added to the theories under consideration, if desired, instead of being considered rules of logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The main difference between this method and first-order logic with equality is that an interpretation may now interpret two distinct individuals as "equal" (although, by Leibniz's law, these will satisfy exactly the same formulas under any interpretation).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] That is, the equality relation may now be interpreted by an arbitrary equivalence relation on the domain of discourse that is congruent with respect to the functions and relations of the interpretation.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] When this second convention is followed, the term *normal model* is used to refer to an interpretation where no distinct individuals *a* and *b* satisfy *a* = *b*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] In first-order logic with equality, only normal models are considered, and so there is no term for a model other than a normal model.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] When first-order logic without equality is studied, it is necessary to amend the statements of results such as the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem so that only normal models are considered.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] First-order logic without equality is often employed in the context of second-order arithmetic and other higher-order theories of arithmetic, where the equality relation between sets of natural numbers is usually omitted.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] If a theory has a binary formula *A*(*x*,*y*) which satisfies reflexivity and Leibniz's law, the theory is said to have equality, or to be a theory with equality.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] The theory may not have all instances of the above schemas as axioms, but rather as derivable theorems.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p01] For example, in theories with no function symbols and a finite number of relations, it is possible to define equality in terms of the relations, by defining the two terms *s* and *t* to be equal if any relation is unchanged by changing *s* to *t* in any argument.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] One motivation for the use of first-order logic, rather than higher-order logic, is that first-order logic has many metalogical properties that stronger logics do not have.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] These results concern general properties of first-order logic itself, rather than properties of individual theories.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] They provide fundamental tools for the construction of models of first-order theories.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Gödel's completeness theorem, proved by Kurt Gödel in 1929, establishes that there are sound, complete, effective deductive systems for first-order logic, and thus the first-order logical consequence relation is captured by finite provability.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Naively, the statement that a formula φ logically implies a formula ψ depends on every model of φ; these models will in general be of arbitrarily large cardinality, and so logical consequence cannot be effectively verified by checking every model.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] However, it is possible to enumerate all finite derivations and search for a derivation of ψ from φ.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] If ψ is logically implied by φ, such a derivation will eventually be found.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Thus first-order logical consequence is semidecidable: it is possible to make an effective enumeration of all pairs of sentences (φ,ψ) such that ψ is a logical consequence of φ.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Unlike propositional logic, first-order logic is undecidable (although semidecidable), provided that the language has at least one predicate of arity at least 2 (other than equality).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] This means that there is no decision procedure that determines whether arbitrary formulas are logically valid.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] This result was established independently by Alonzo Church and Alan Turing in 1936 and 1937, respectively, giving a negative answer to the Entscheidungsproblem posed by David Hilbert and Wilhelm Ackermann in 1928.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Their proofs demonstrate a connection between the unsolvability of the decision problem for first-order logic and the unsolvability of the halting problem.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] There are systems weaker than full first-order logic for which the logical consequence relation is decidable.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] These include propositional logic and monadic predicate logic, which is first-order logic restricted to unary predicate symbols and no function symbols.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Other logics with no function symbols which are decidable are the guarded fragment of first-order logic, as well as two-variable logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The Bernays–Schönfinkel class of first-order formulas is also decidable.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Decidable subsets of first-order logic are also studied in the framework of description logics.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] See (Pratt-Hartmann, 2023) for a monograph.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem shows that if a first-order theory of cardinality λ has an infinite model, then it has models of every infinite cardinality greater than or equal to λ.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] One of the earliest results in model theory, it implies that it is not possible to characterize countability or uncountability in a first-order language with a countable signature.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] That is, there is no first-order formula φ(*x*) such that an arbitrary structure M satisfies φ if and only if the domain of discourse of M is countable (or, in the second case, uncountable).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem implies that infinite structures cannot be categorically axiomatized in first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For example, there is no first-order theory whose only model is the real line: any first-order theory with an infinite model also has a model of cardinality larger than the continuum.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Since the real line is infinite, any theory satisfied by the real line is also satisfied by some nonstandard models.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] When the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem is applied to first-order set theories, the nonintuitive consequences are known as Skolem's paradox.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The compactness theorem states that a set of first-order sentences has a model if and only if every finite subset of it has a model.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] This implies that if a formula is a logical consequence of an infinite set of first-order axioms, then it is a logical consequence of some finite number of those axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] This theorem was proved first by Kurt Gödel as a consequence of the completeness theorem, but many additional proofs have been obtained over time.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] It is a central tool in model theory, providing a fundamental method for constructing models.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The compactness theorem has a limiting effect on which collections of first-order structures are elementary classes.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For example, the compactness theorem implies that any theory that has arbitrarily large finite models has an infinite model.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Thus, the class of all finite graphs is not an elementary class (the same holds for many other algebraic structures).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] There are also more subtle limitations of first-order logic that are implied by the compactness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For example, in computer science, many situations can be modeled as a directed graph of states (nodes) and connections (directed edges).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Validating such a system may require showing that no "bad" state can be reached from any "good" state.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Thus, one seeks to determine if the good and bad states are in different connected components of the graph.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] However, the compactness theorem can be used to show that connected graphs are not an elementary class in first-order logic, and there is no formula φ(*x*,*y*) of first-order logic, in the logic of graphs, that expresses the idea that there is a path from *x* to *y*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Connectedness can be expressed in second-order logic, however, but not with only existential set quantifiers, as $\Sigma _{1}^{1}$ also enjoys compactness.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Per Lindström showed that the metalogical properties just discussed actually characterize first-order logic in the sense that no stronger logic can also have those properties (Ebbinghaus and Flum 1994, Chapter XIII).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Lindström defined a class of abstract logical systems, and a rigorous definition of the relative strength of a member of this class.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Although first-order logic is sufficient for formalizing much of mathematics and is commonly used in computer science and other fields, it has certain limitations.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] These include limitations on its expressiveness and limitations of the fragments of natural languages that it can describe.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem shows that if a first-order theory has any infinite model, then it has infinite models of every cardinality.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] In particular, no first-order theory with an infinite model can be categorical.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Thus, there is no first-order theory whose only model has the set of natural numbers as its domain, or whose only model has the set of real numbers as its domain.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Many extensions of first-order logic, including infinitary logics and higher-order logics, are more expressive in the sense that they do permit categorical axiomatizations of the natural numbers or real numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] This expressiveness comes at a metalogical cost, however: by Lindström's theorem, the compactness theorem and the downward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem cannot hold in any logic stronger than first-order.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] First-order logic is able to formalize many simple quantifier constructions in natural language, such as "every person who lives in Perth lives in Australia".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Hence, first-order logic is used as a basis for knowledge representation languages, such as FO(.).
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Still, there are complicated features of natural language that cannot be expressed in first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] "Any logical system which is appropriate as an instrument for the analysis of natural language needs a much richer structure than first-order predicate logic".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] There are many variations of first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Some of these are inessential in the sense that they merely change notation without affecting the semantics.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Others change the expressive power more significantly, by extending the semantics through additional quantifiers or other new logical symbols.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For example, infinitary logics permit formulas of infinite size, and modal logics add symbols for possibility and necessity.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Restrictions such as these are useful as a technique to reduce the number of inference rules or axiom schemas in deductive systems, which leads to shorter proofs of metalogical results.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Similarly, derivations in the limited systems may be longer than derivations in systems that include additional connectives.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] There is thus a trade-off between the ease of working within the formal system and the ease of proving results about the formal system.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] It is also possible to restrict the arities of function symbols and predicate symbols, in sufficiently expressive theories.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] One can in principle dispense entirely with functions of arity greater than 2 and predicates of arity greater than 1 in theories that include a pairing function.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] This is a function of arity 2 that takes pairs of elements of the domain and returns an ordered pair containing them.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] It is also sufficient to have two predicate symbols of arity 2 that define projection functions from an ordered pair to its components.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] In either case it is necessary that the natural axioms for a pairing function and its projections are satisfied.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Ordinary first-order interpretations have a single domain of discourse over which all quantifiers range.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] *Many-sorted first-order logic* allows variables to have different *sorts*, which have different domains.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] This is also called *typed first-order logic*, and the sorts called *types* (as in data type), but it is not the same as first-order type theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Many-sorted first-order logic is often used in the study of second-order arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] When there are only finitely many sorts in a theory, many-sorted first-order logic can be reduced to single-sorted first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] One introduces into the single-sorted theory a unary predicate symbol for each sort in the many-sorted theory and adds an axiom saying that these unary predicates partition the domain of discourse.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Then the elements satisfying $P_{1}$ are thought of as elements of the first sort, and elements satisfying $P_{2}$ as elements of the second sort.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] One can quantify over each sort by using the corresponding predicate symbol to limit the range of quantification.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Additional quantifiers can be added to first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Infinitary logic allows infinitely long sentences.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For example, one may allow a conjunction or disjunction of infinitely many formulas, or quantification over infinitely many variables.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Infinitely long sentences arise in areas of mathematics including topology and model theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Infinitary logic generalizes first-order logic to allow formulas of infinite length.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The most common way in which formulas can become infinite is through infinite conjunctions and disjunctions.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] However, it is also possible to admit generalized signatures in which function and relation symbols are allowed to have infinite arities, or in which quantifiers can bind infinitely many variables.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Because an infinite formula cannot be represented by a finite string, it is necessary to choose some other representation of formulas; the usual representation in this context is a tree.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Thus, formulas are, essentially, identified with their parse trees, rather than with the strings being parsed.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The most commonly studied infinitary logics are denoted *L*αβ, where α and β are each either cardinal numbers or the symbol ∞.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] In this notation, ordinary first-order logic is *L*ωω.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] In the logic *L*∞ω, arbitrary conjunctions or disjunctions are allowed when building formulas, and there is an unlimited supply of variables.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] More generally, the logic that permits conjunctions or disjunctions with less than κ constituents is known as *L*κω.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For example, *L*ω1ω permits countable conjunctions and disjunctions.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The set of free variables in a formula of *L*κω can have any cardinality strictly less than κ, yet only finitely many of them can be in the scope of any quantifier when a formula appears as a subformula of another.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] In other infinitary logics, a subformula may be in the scope of infinitely many quantifiers.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For example, in *L*κ∞, a single universal or existential quantifier may bind arbitrarily many variables simultaneously.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Similarly, the logic *L*κλ permits simultaneous quantification over fewer than λ variables, as well as conjunctions and disjunctions of size less than κ.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Fixpoint logic extends first-order logic by adding the closure under the least fixed points of positive operators.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The characteristic feature of first-order logic is that individuals can be quantified, but not predicates.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] is not, in most formalizations of first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Second-order logic extends first-order logic by adding the latter type of quantification.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Other higher-order logics allow quantification over even higher types than second-order logic permits.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] These higher types include relations between relations, functions from relations to relations between relations, and other higher-type objects.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Thus the "first" in first-order logic describes the type of objects that can be quantified.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Unlike first-order logic, for which only one semantics is studied, there are several possible semantics for second-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The most commonly employed semantics for second-order and higher-order logic is known as *full semantics*.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The combination of additional quantifiers and the full semantics for these quantifiers makes higher-order logic stronger than first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] In particular, the (semantic) logical consequence relation for second-order and higher-order logic is not semidecidable; there is no effective deduction system for second-order logic that is sound and complete under full semantics.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Second-order logic with full semantics is more expressive than first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For example, it is possible to create axiom systems in second-order logic that uniquely characterize the natural numbers and the real line.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The cost of this expressiveness is that second-order and higher-order logics have fewer attractive metalogical properties than first-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For example, the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem and compactness theorem of first-order logic become false when generalized to higher-order logics with full semantics.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Automated theorem proving refers to the development of computer programs that search and find derivations (formal proofs) of mathematical theorems.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Finding derivations is a difficult task because the search space can be very large; an exhaustive search of every possible derivation is theoretically possible but computationally infeasible for many systems of interest in mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Thus complicated heuristic functions are developed to attempt to find a derivation in less time than a blind search.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] The related area of automated proof verification uses computer programs to check that human-created proofs are correct.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Unlike complicated automated theorem provers, verification systems may be small enough that their correctness can be checked both by hand and through automated software verification.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] This validation of the proof verifier is needed to give confidence that any derivation labeled as "correct" is actually correct.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Some proof verifiers, such as Metamath, insist on having a complete derivation as input.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Others, such as Mizar and Isabelle, take a well-formatted proof sketch (which may still be very long and detailed) and fill in the missing pieces by doing simple proof searches or applying known decision procedures: the resulting derivation is then verified by a small core "kernel".
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Many such systems are primarily intended for interactive use by human mathematicians: these are known as proof assistants.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] They may also use formal logics that are stronger than first-order logic, such as type theory.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Because a full derivation of any nontrivial result in a first-order deductive system will be extremely long for a human to write, results are often formalized as a series of lemmas, for which derivations can be constructed separately.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Automated theorem provers are also used to implement formal verification in computer science.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] In this setting, theorem provers are used to verify the correctness of programs and of hardware such as processors with respect to a formal specification.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] Because such analysis is time-consuming and thus expensive, it is usually reserved for projects in which a malfunction would have grave human or financial consequences.
[src:logic-foundations/first-order-logic-p02] For the problem of model checking, efficient algorithms are known to decide whether an input finite structure satisfies a first-order formula, in addition to computational complexity bounds: see Model checking § First-order logic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The first incompleteness theorem states that no consistent system of axioms whose theorems can be listed by an effective procedure (i.e. an algorithm) is capable of proving all truths about the arithmetic of natural numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For any such consistent formal system, there will always be statements about natural numbers that are true, but that are unprovable within the system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Equivalently, there will always be statements about natural numbers that are false, but that cannot be proved false within the system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The second incompleteness theorem, an extension of the first, shows that no such system can demonstrate its own consistency.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Employing a diagonal argument, Gödel's incompleteness theorems were among the first of several closely related theorems on the limitations of formal systems.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] They were followed by Tarski's undefinability theorem on the formal undefinability of truth, Church's proof that Hilbert's *Entscheidungsproblem* is unsolvable, and Turing's theorem that there is no algorithm to solve the halting problem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The incompleteness theorems apply to formal systems that are of sufficient complexity to express the basic arithmetic of the natural numbers and which are consistent and effectively axiomatized.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Particularly in the context of first-order logic, formal systems are also called *formal theories*.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In general, a formal system is a deductive apparatus that consists of a particular set of axioms along with rules of symbolic manipulation (or rules of inference) that allow for the derivation of new theorems from the axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] One example of such a system is first-order Peano arithmetic, a system in which all variables are intended to denote natural numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In other systems, such as set theory, only some sentences of the formal system express statements about the natural numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The incompleteness theorems are about formal provability *within* these systems, rather than about "provability" in an informal sense.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] There are several properties that a formal system may have, including completeness, consistency, and the existence of an effective axiomatization.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The incompleteness theorems show that systems which contain a sufficient amount of arithmetic cannot possess all three of these properties.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A formal system is said to be *effectively axiomatized* (also called *effectively generated*) if its set of theorems is recursively enumerable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This means that there is a computer program that, in principle, could enumerate all the theorems of the system without listing any statements that are not theorems.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Examples of effectively generated theories include Peano arithmetic and Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (ZFC).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The theory known as true arithmetic consists of all true statements about the standard integers in the language of Peano arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This theory is consistent and complete, and contains a sufficient amount of arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] However, it does not have a recursively enumerable set of axioms, and thus does not satisfy the hypotheses of the incompleteness theorems.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A set of axioms is (*syntactically*, or *negation*-) complete if, for any statement in the axioms' language, that statement or its negation is provable from the axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This is the notion relevant for Gödel's first Incompleteness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] It is not to be confused with *semantic* completeness, which means that the set of axioms proves all the semantic tautologies of the given language.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In his completeness theorem (not to be confused with the incompleteness theorems described here), Gödel proved that first-order logic is *semantically* complete.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] But it is not syntactically complete, since there are sentences expressible in the language of first-order logic that can be neither proved nor disproved from the axioms of logic alone.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In a system of mathematics, thinkers such as Hilbert believed that it was just a matter of time to find such an axiomatization that would allow one to either prove or disprove (by proving its negation) every mathematical formula.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A formal system might be syntactically incomplete by design, as logics generally are.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Or it may be incomplete simply because not all the necessary axioms have been discovered or included.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For example, Euclidean geometry without the parallel postulate is incomplete, because some statements in the language (such as the parallel postulate itself) can not be proved from the remaining axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Similarly, the theory of dense linear orders is not complete, but becomes complete with an extra axiom stating that there are no endpoints in the order.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The continuum hypothesis is a statement in the language of ZFC that is not provable within ZFC, so ZFC is not complete.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In this case, there is no obvious candidate for a new axiom that resolves the issue.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The theory of first-order Peano arithmetic seems consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Assuming this is indeed the case, note that it has an infinite but recursively enumerable set of axioms, and can encode enough arithmetic for the hypotheses of the incompleteness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Thus by the first incompleteness theorem, Peano Arithmetic is not complete.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The theorem gives an explicit example of a statement of arithmetic that is neither provable nor disprovable in Peano's arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Moreover, this statement is true in the usual model.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In addition, no effectively axiomatized, consistent extension of Peano arithmetic can be complete.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A set of axioms is (simply) consistent if there is no statement such that both the statement and its negation are provable from the axioms, and *inconsistent* otherwise.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] That is to say, a consistent axiomatic system is one that is free from contradiction.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Peano arithmetic is provably consistent from ZFC, but not from within itself.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] If one takes all statements in the language of Peano arithmetic as axioms, then this theory is complete, has a recursively enumerable set of axioms, and can describe addition and multiplication.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Additional examples of inconsistent theories arise from the paradoxes that result when the axiom schema of unrestricted comprehension is assumed in set theory.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The incompleteness theorems apply only to formal systems which are able to prove a sufficient collection of facts about the natural numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] One sufficient collection is the set of theorems of Robinson arithmetic Q.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Some systems, such as Peano arithmetic, can directly express statements about natural numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Others, such as ZFC set theory, are able to interpret statements about natural numbers into their language.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Either of these options is appropriate for the incompleteness theorems.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The theory of algebraically closed fields of a given characteristic is complete, consistent, and has an infinite but recursively enumerable set of axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] However it is not possible to encode the integers into this theory, and the theory cannot describe arithmetic of integers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A similar example is the theory of real closed fields, which is essentially equivalent to Tarski's axioms for Euclidean geometry.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] So Euclidean geometry itself (in Tarski's formulation) is an example of a complete, consistent, effectively axiomatized theory.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The system of Presburger arithmetic consists of a set of axioms for the natural numbers with just the addition operation (multiplication is omitted).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Presburger arithmetic is complete, consistent, and recursively enumerable and can encode addition but not multiplication of natural numbers, showing that for Gödel's theorems one needs the theory to encode not just addition but also multiplication.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In choosing a set of axioms, one goal is to be able to prove as many correct results as possible, without proving any incorrect results.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For example, we could imagine a set of true axioms which allow us to prove every true arithmetical claim about the natural numbers (Smith 2007, p.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In the standard system of first-order logic, an inconsistent set of axioms will prove every statement in its language (this is sometimes called the principle of explosion), and is thus automatically complete.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A set of axioms that is both complete and consistent, however, proves a maximal set of non-contradictory theorems.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The pattern illustrated in the previous sections with Peano arithmetic, ZFC, and ZFC + "there exists an inaccessible cardinal" cannot generally be broken.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Here ZFC + "there exists an inaccessible cardinal" cannot from itself, be proved consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] It is also not complete, as illustrated by the continuum hypothesis, which is unresolvable in ZFC + "there exists an inaccessible cardinal".
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] If an axiom is ever added that makes the system complete, it does so at the cost of making the system inconsistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] It is not even possible for an infinite list of axioms to be complete, consistent, and effectively axiomatized.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The unprovable statement *G**F* referred to by the theorem is often referred to as "the Gödel sentence" for the system F.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The proof constructs a particular Gödel sentence for the system F, but there are infinitely many statements in the language of the system that share the same properties, such as the conjunction of the Gödel sentence and any logically valid sentence.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Each effectively generated system has its own Gödel sentence.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] It is possible to define a larger system F' that contains the whole of F plus *G**F* as an additional axiom.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This will not result in a complete system, because Gödel's theorem will also apply to F', and thus F' also cannot be complete.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In this case, *G**F* is indeed a theorem in F', because it is an axiom.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Because *G**F* states only that it is not provable in F, no contradiction is presented by its provability within F'.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] However, because the incompleteness theorem applies to F', there will be a new Gödel statement *G**F* ' for F', showing that F' is also incomplete.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] *G**F* ' will differ from *G**F* in that *G**F* ' will refer to F', rather than F.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The Gödel sentence is designed to refer, indirectly, to itself.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The sentence states that, when a particular sequence of steps is used to construct another sentence, that constructed sentence will not be provable in F.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] However, the sequence of steps is such that the constructed sentence turns out to be *G**F* itself.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In this way, the Gödel sentence *G**F* indirectly states its own unprovability within F.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] To prove the first incompleteness theorem, Gödel demonstrated that the notion of provability within a system could be expressed purely in terms of arithmetical functions that operate on Gödel numbers of sentences of the system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Therefore, the system, which can prove certain facts about numbers, can also indirectly prove facts about its own statements, provided that it is effectively generated.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Questions about the provability of statements within the system are represented as questions about the arithmetical properties of numbers themselves, which would be decidable by the system if it were complete.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Thus, although the Gödel sentence refers indirectly to sentences of the system F, when read as an arithmetical statement the Gödel sentence directly refers only to natural numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] It asserts that no natural number has a particular property, where that property is given by a primitive recursive relation (Smith 2007, p.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] As such, the Gödel sentence can be written in the language of arithmetic with a simple syntactic form.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In particular, it can be expressed as a formula in the language of arithmetic consisting of a number of leading universal quantifiers followed by a quantifier-free body (these formulas are at level $\Pi _{1}^{0}$ of the arithmetical hierarchy).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Via the MRDP theorem, the Gödel sentence can be re-written as a statement that a particular polynomial in many variables with integer coefficients never takes the value zero when integers are substituted for its variables (Franzén 2005, p.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The first incompleteness theorem shows that the Gödel sentence *G**F* of an appropriate formal theory F is unprovable in F.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Because, when interpreted as a statement about arithmetic, this unprovability is exactly what the sentence (indirectly) asserts, the Gödel sentence is, in fact, true (Smoryński 1977, p.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For this reason, the sentence *G**F* is often said to be "true but unprovable." (Raatikainen 2020).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] However, since the Gödel sentence cannot itself formally specify its intended interpretation, the truth of the sentence *G**F* may only be arrived at via a meta-analysis from outside the system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In general, this meta-analysis can be carried out within the weak formal system known as primitive recursive arithmetic, which proves the implication *Con*(*F*)→*G*F, where *Con*(*F*) is a canonical sentence asserting the consistency of F (Smoryński 1977, p.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Although the Gödel sentence of a consistent theory is true as a statement about the intended interpretation of arithmetic, the Gödel sentence will be false in some nonstandard models of arithmetic, as a consequence of Gödel's completeness theorem (Franzén 2005, p.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] That theorem shows that, when a sentence is independent of a theory, the theory will have models in which the sentence is true and models in which the sentence is false.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] As described earlier, the Gödel sentence of a system F is an arithmetical statement which claims that no number exists with a particular property.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The incompleteness theorem shows that this claim will be independent of the system F, and the truth of the Gödel sentence follows from the fact that no standard natural number has the property in question.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Any model in which the Gödel sentence is false must contain some element which satisfies the property within that model.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Such a model must be "nonstandard" – it must contain elements that do not correspond to any standard natural number (Raatikainen 2020, Franzén 2005, p.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gödel specifically cites Richard's paradox and the liar paradox as semantical analogues to his syntactical incompleteness result in the introductory section of "On Formally Undecidable Propositions in Principia Mathematica and Related Systems I".
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The liar paradox is the sentence "This sentence is false." An analysis of the liar sentence shows that it cannot be true (for then, as it asserts, it is false), nor can it be false (for then, it is true).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A Gödel sentence G for a system F makes a similar assertion to the liar sentence, but with truth replaced by provability: G says "G is not provable in the system F." The analysis of the truth and provability of G is a formalized version of the analysis of the truth of the liar sentence.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] It is not possible to replace "not provable" with "false" in a Gödel sentence because the predicate "Q is the Gödel number of a false formula" cannot be represented as a formula of arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This result, known as Tarski's undefinability theorem, was discovered independently both by Gödel, when he was working on the proof of the incompleteness theorem, and by the theorem's namesake, Alfred Tarski.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Compared to the theorems stated in Gödel's 1931 paper, many contemporary statements of the incompleteness theorems are more general in two ways.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] These generalized statements are phrased to apply to a broader class of systems, and they are phrased to incorporate weaker consistency assumptions.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gödel demonstrated the incompleteness of the system of *Principia Mathematica*, a particular system of arithmetic, but a parallel demonstration could be given for any effective system of a certain expressiveness.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gödel commented on this fact in the introduction to his paper, but restricted the proof to one system for concreteness.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In modern statements of the theorem, it is common to state the effectiveness and expressiveness conditions as hypotheses for the incompleteness theorem, so that it is not limited to any particular formal system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The terminology used to state these conditions was not yet developed in 1931 when Gödel published his results.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gödel's original statement and proof of the incompleteness theorem requires the assumption that the system is not just consistent but *ω-consistent*.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A system is **ω-consistent** if it is not ω-inconsistent, and is ω-inconsistent if there is a predicate P such that for every specific natural number m the system proves ~*P*(*m*), and yet the system also proves that there exists a natural number n such that P(n).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] That is, the system says that a number with property P exists while denying that it has any specific value.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The ω-consistency of a system implies its consistency, but consistency does not imply ω-consistency.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Barkley Rosser (1936) strengthened the incompleteness theorem by finding a variation of the proof (Rosser's trick) that only requires the system to be consistent, rather than ω-consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This is mostly of technical interest, because all true formal theories of arithmetic (theories whose axioms are all true statements about natural numbers) are ω-consistent, and thus Gödel's theorem as originally stated applies to them.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The stronger version of the incompleteness theorem that only assumes consistency, rather than ω-consistency, has become commonly known as Gödel's incompleteness theorem and as the Gödel–Rosser theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For each formal system F containing basic arithmetic, it is possible to canonically define a formula Cons(F) expressing the consistency of F.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] There is a technical subtlety in the second incompleteness theorem regarding the method of expressing the consistency of F as a formula in the language of F.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] There are many ways to express the consistency of a system, and not all of them lead to the same result.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The formula Cons(F) from the second incompleteness theorem is a particular expression of consistency.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Other formalizations of the claim that F is consistent may be inequivalent in F, and some may even be provable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For example, first-order Peano arithmetic (PA) can prove that "the largest consistent subset of PA" is consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] But, because PA is consistent, the largest consistent subset of PA is just PA, so in this sense PA "proves that it is consistent".
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] What PA does not prove is that the largest consistent subset of PA is, in fact, the whole of PA.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The standard proof of the second incompleteness theorem assumes that the provability predicate *Prov*A(*P*) satisfies the Hilbert–Bernays provability conditions.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] There are systems, such as Robinson arithmetic, which are strong enough to meet the assumptions of the first incompleteness theorem, but which do not prove the Hilbert–Bernays conditions.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Peano arithmetic, however, is strong enough to verify these conditions, as are all theories stronger than Peano arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gödel's second incompleteness theorem also implies that a system *F*1 satisfying the technical conditions outlined above cannot prove the consistency of any system *F*2 that proves the consistency of *F*1.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This is because such a system *F*1 can prove that if *F*2 proves the consistency of *F*1, then *F*1 is in fact consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For the claim that *F*1 is consistent has form "for all numbers n, n has the decidable property of not being a code for a proof of contradiction in *F*1".
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] If *F*1 were in fact inconsistent, then *F*2 would prove for some n that n is the code of a contradiction in *F*1.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] But if *F*2 also proved that *F*1 is consistent (that is, that there is no such n), then it would itself be inconsistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This reasoning can be formalized in *F*1 to show that if *F*2 is consistent, then *F*1 is consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Since, by second incompleteness theorem, *F*1 does not prove its consistency, it cannot prove the consistency of *F*2 either.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This corollary of the second incompleteness theorem shows that there is no hope of proving, for example, the consistency of Peano arithmetic using any finitistic means that can be formalized in a system the consistency of which is provable in Peano arithmetic (PA).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For example, the system of primitive recursive arithmetic (PRA), which is widely accepted as an accurate formalization of finitistic mathematics, is provably consistent in PA.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Thus PRA cannot prove the consistency of PA.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This fact is generally seen to imply that Hilbert's program, which aimed to justify the use of "ideal" (infinitistic) mathematical principles in the proofs of "real" (finitistic) mathematical statements by giving a finitistic proof that the ideal principles are consistent, cannot be carried out.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The corollary also indicates the epistemological relevance of the second incompleteness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] It would provide no interesting information if a system F proved its consistency.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This is because inconsistent theories prove everything, including their consistency.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Thus a consistency proof of F in F would give us no clue as to whether F is consistent; no doubts about the consistency of F would be resolved by such a consistency proof.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The interest in consistency proofs lies in the possibility of proving the consistency of a system F in some system F' that is in some sense less doubtful than F itself, for example, weaker than F.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For many naturally occurring theories F and F', such as F = Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory and F' = primitive recursive arithmetic, the consistency of F' is provable in F, and thus F' cannot prove the consistency of F by the above corollary of the second incompleteness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The second incompleteness theorem does not rule out altogether the possibility of proving the consistency of a different system with different axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For example, Gerhard Gentzen proved the consistency of Peano arithmetic in a different system that includes an axiom asserting that the ordinal called *ε*0 is wellfounded; see Gentzen's consistency proof.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gentzen's theorem spurred the development of ordinal analysis in proof theory.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] There are two distinct senses of the word "undecidable" in mathematics and computer science.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The first of these is the proof-theoretic sense used in relation to Gödel's theorems, that of a statement being neither provable nor refutable in a specified deductive system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The second sense, which will not be discussed here, is used in relation to computability theory and applies not to statements but to decision problems, which are countably infinite sets of questions each requiring a yes or no answer.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Such a problem is said to be undecidable if there is no computable function that correctly answers every question in the problem set (see undecidable problem).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Because of the two meanings of the word undecidable, the term independent is sometimes used instead of undecidable for the "neither provable nor refutable" sense.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Undecidability of a statement in a particular deductive system does not, in and of itself, address the question of whether the truth value of the statement is well-defined, or whether it can be determined by other means.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Undecidability only implies that the particular deductive system being considered does not prove the truth or falsity of the statement.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Whether there exist so-called "absolutely undecidable" statements, whose truth value can never be known or is ill-specified, is a controversial point in the philosophy of mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] These results do not require the incompleteness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gödel proved in 1940 that neither of these statements could be disproved in ZF or ZFC set theory.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In the 1960s, Cohen proved that neither is provable from ZF, and the continuum hypothesis cannot be proved from ZFC.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Shelah (1974) showed that the Whitehead problem in group theory is undecidable, in the first sense of the term, in standard set theory.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gregory Chaitin produced undecidable statements in algorithmic information theory and proved another incompleteness theorem in that setting.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Chaitin's incompleteness theorem states that for any system that can represent enough arithmetic, there is an upper bound c such that no specific number can be proved in that system to have Kolmogorov complexity greater than c.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] While Gödel's theorem is related to the liar paradox, Chaitin's result is related to Berry's paradox.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] These are natural mathematical equivalents of the Gödel "true but undecidable" sentence.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] They can be proved in a larger system which is generally accepted as a valid form of reasoning, but are undecidable in a more limited system such as Peano Arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In 1977, Paris and Harrington proved that the Paris–Harrington principle, a version of the infinite Ramsey theorem, is undecidable in (first-order) Peano arithmetic, but can be proved in the stronger system of second-order arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Kirby and Paris later showed that Goodstein's theorem, a statement about sequences of natural numbers somewhat simpler than the Paris–Harrington principle, is also undecidable in Peano arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Kruskal's tree theorem, which has applications in computer science, is also undecidable from Peano arithmetic but provable in set theory.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In fact Kruskal's tree theorem (or its finite form) is undecidable in a much stronger system ATR0 codifying the principles acceptable based on a philosophy of mathematics called predicativism.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The related but more general graph minor theorem (2003) has consequences for computational complexity theory.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The incompleteness theorem is closely related to several results about undecidable sets in recursion theory.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Kleene (1943) presented a proof of Gödel's incompleteness theorem using basic results of computability theory.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] One such result shows that the halting problem is undecidable: no computer program can correctly determine, given any program P as input, whether P eventually halts when run with a particular given input.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Kleene showed that the existence of a complete effective system of arithmetic with certain consistency properties would force the halting problem to be decidable, a contradiction.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This method of proof has also been presented by Shoenfield (1967); Charlesworth (1981); and Hopcroft & Ullman (1979).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Franzén (2005) explains how Matiyasevich's solution to Hilbert's 10th problem can be used to obtain a proof to Gödel's first incompleteness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Matiyasevich proved that there is no algorithm that, given a multivariate polynomial *p*(*x*1, *x*2,...,*x*k) with integer coefficients, determines whether there is an integer solution to the equation p = 0.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Because polynomials with integer coefficients, and integers themselves, are directly expressible in the language of arithmetic, if a multivariate integer polynomial equation p = 0 does have a solution in the integers then any sufficiently strong system of arithmetic T will prove this.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Moreover, suppose the system T is ω-consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In that case, it will never prove that a particular polynomial equation has a solution when there is no solution in the integers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Thus, if T were complete and ω-consistent, it would be possible to determine algorithmically whether a polynomial equation has a solution by merely enumerating proofs of T until either "p has a solution" or "p has no solution" is found, in contradiction to Matiyasevich's theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Hence it follows that T cannot be ω-consistent and complete.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Moreover, for each consistent effectively generated system T, it is possible to effectively generate a multivariate polynomial p over the integers such that the equation p = 0 has no solutions over the integers, but the lack of solutions cannot be proved in T.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Smoryński (1977) shows how the existence of recursively inseparable sets can be used to prove the first incompleteness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This proof is often extended to show that systems such as Peano arithmetic are essentially undecidable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Chaitin's incompleteness theorem gives a different method of producing independent sentences, based on Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Like the proof presented by Kleene that was mentioned above, Chaitin's theorem only applies to theories with the additional property that all their axioms are true in the standard model of the natural numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gödel's incompleteness theorem is distinguished by its applicability to consistent theories that nonetheless include false statements in the standard model; these theories are known as ω-inconsistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The proof by contradiction has three essential parts.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In the formal system it is possible to construct a number whose matching statement, when interpreted, is self-referential and essentially says that it (i.e. the statement itself) is unprovable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This is done using a technique called "diagonalization" (so-called because of its origins as Cantor's diagonal argument).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Within the formal system this statement permits a demonstration that it is neither provable nor disprovable in the system, and therefore the system cannot in fact be ω-consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Hence the original assumption that the proposed system met the criteria is false.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The main problem in fleshing out the proof just described is that it seems at first that to construct a statement p that is equivalent to "p cannot be proved", p would somehow have to contain a reference to p, which could easily give rise to an infinite regress.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gödel's technique is to show that statements can be matched with numbers (often called the arithmetization of syntax) in such a way that *"proving a statement"* can be replaced with *"testing whether a number has a given property"*.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This allows a self-referential formula to be constructed in a way that avoids any infinite regress of definitions.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The same technique was later used by Alan Turing in his work on the *Entscheidungsproblem*.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In simple terms, a method can be devised so that every formula or statement that can be formulated in the system gets a unique number, called its Gödel number, in such a way that it is possible to mechanically convert back and forth between formulas and Gödel numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The numbers involved might be very long indeed (in terms of number of digits), but this is not a barrier; all that matters is that such numbers can be constructed.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In principle, proving a statement true or false can be shown to be equivalent to proving that the number matching the statement does or does not have a given property.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Because the formal system is strong enough to support reasoning about *numbers in general*, it can support reasoning about *numbers that represent formulae and statements* as well.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Crucially, because the system can support reasoning about *properties of numbers*, the results are equivalent to reasoning about *provability of their equivalent statements*.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Having shown that in principle the system can indirectly make statements about provability, by analyzing properties of those numbers representing statements it is possible to show how to create a statement that actually does this.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A formula *F*(*x*) that contains exactly one free variable x is called a *statement form* or *class-sign*.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] As soon as x is replaced by a specific number, the statement form turns into a *bona fide* statement, and it is then either provable in the system, or not.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] For certain formulas one can show that for every natural number n, ⁠ $F(n)$ ⁠ is true if and only if it can be proved (the precise requirement in the original proof is weaker, but for the proof sketch this will suffice).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In particular, this is true for every specific arithmetic operation between a finite number of natural numbers, such as "2 × 3 = 6".
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Statement forms themselves are not statements and therefore cannot be proved or disproved.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] But every statement form *F*(*x*) can be assigned a Gödel number denoted by **G**(*F*).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The choice of the free variable used in the form F(x) is not relevant to the assignment of the Gödel number **G**(*F*).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The notion of provability itself can also be encoded by Gödel numbers, in the following way: since a proof is a list of statements which obey certain rules, the Gödel number of a proof can be defined.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Then, for every statement p, one may ask whether a number x is the Gödel number of its proof.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The relation between the Gödel number of p and x, the potential Gödel number of its proof, is an arithmetical relation between two numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The name **Bew** is short for *beweisbar*, the German word for "provable"; this name was originally used by Gödel to denote the provability formula just described.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Note that "*Bew*(*y*)" is merely an abbreviation that represents a particular, very long, formula in the original language of T; the string "Bew" itself is not claimed to be part of this language.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] An important feature of the formula *Bew*(*y*) is that if a statement p is provable in the system then *Bew*(**G**(*p*)) is also provable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This is because any proof of p would have a corresponding Gödel number, the existence of which causes Bew(**G**(*p*)) to be satisfied.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The next step in the proof is to obtain a statement which, indirectly, asserts its own unprovability.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] and the p defined by this roughly states that its own Gödel number is the Gödel number of an unprovable formula.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The statement p is not literally equal to ~*Bew*(**G**(*p*)); rather, p states that if a certain calculation is performed, the resulting Gödel number will be that of an unprovable statement.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] But when this calculation is performed, the resulting Gödel number turns out to be the Gödel number of p itself.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] ", when preceded by itself in quotes, is unprovable.", when preceded by itself in quotes, is unprovable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This sentence does not directly refer to itself, but when the stated transformation is made the original sentence is obtained as a result, and thus this sentence indirectly asserts its own unprovability.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The proof of the diagonal lemma employs a similar method.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Next, assume that the axiomatic system is ω-consistent, and let p be the statement obtained in the previous section.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] If p were provable, then *Bew*(**G**(*p*)) would be provable, as argued above.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] But p asserts the negation of *Bew*(**G**(*p*)).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Thus the system would be inconsistent, proving both a statement and its negation.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This contradiction shows that p cannot be provable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] If the negation of p were provable, then *Bew*(**G**(*p*)) would be provable (because p was constructed to be equivalent to the negation of *Bew*(**G**(*p*))).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] However, for each specific number x, x cannot be the Gödel number of the proof of p, because p is not provable (from the previous paragraph).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Thus on one hand the system proves there is a number with a certain property (that it is the Gödel number of the proof of p), but on the other hand, for every specific number x, we can prove that it does not have this property.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This is impossible in an ω-consistent system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Thus the statement p is undecidable in our axiomatic system: it can neither be proved nor disproved within the system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] In fact, to show that p is not provable only requires the assumption that the system is consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The stronger assumption of ω-consistency is required to show that the negation of p is not provable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] If one tries to "add the missing axioms" to avoid the incompleteness of the system, then one has to add either p or "not p" as axioms.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] But then the definition of "being a Gödel number of a proof" of a statement changes. which means that the formula *Bew*(*x*) is now different.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Thus when we apply the diagonal lemma to this new Bew, we obtain a new statement p, different from the previous one, which will be undecidable in the new system if it is ω-consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Boolos (1989) sketches an alternative proof of the first incompleteness theorem that uses Berry's paradox rather than the liar paradox to construct a true but unprovable formula.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A similar proof method was independently discovered by Saul Kripke.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Boolos's proof proceeds by constructing, for any computably enumerable set S of true sentences of arithmetic, another sentence which is true but not contained in S.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This gives the first incompleteness theorem as a corollary.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] According to Boolos, this proof is interesting because it provides a "different sort of reason" for the incompleteness of effective, consistent theories of arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The incompleteness theorems are among a relatively small number of nontrivial theorems that have been transformed into formalized theorems that can be completely verified by proof assistant software.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Gödel's original proofs of the incompleteness theorems, like most mathematical proofs, were written in natural language intended for human readers.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Computer-verified proofs of versions of the first incompleteness theorem were announced by Natarajan Shankar in 1986 using Nqthm (Shankar 1994), by Russell O'Connor in 2003 using Rocq (previously known as *Coq*) (O'Connor 2005) and by John Harrison in 2009 using HOL Light (Harrison 2009).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] A computer-verified proof of both incompleteness theorems was announced by Lawrence Paulson in 2013 using Isabelle (Paulson 2014).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The main difficulty in proving the second incompleteness theorem is to show that various facts about provability used in the proof of the first incompleteness theorem can be formalized within a system S using a formal predicate *P* for provability.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Once this is done, the second incompleteness theorem follows by formalizing the entire proof of the first incompleteness theorem within the system S itself.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Let p stand for the undecidable sentence constructed above, and assume for purposes of obtaining a contradiction that the consistency of the system S can be proved from within the system S itself.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] This is equivalent to proving the statement "System S is consistent".
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Next consider the statement c, where c = "If the system S is consistent, then p is not provable".
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] The proof of sentence c can be formalized within the system S, and therefore the statement c, "p is not provable", (or identically, "not *P*(*p*)") can be proved in the system S.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Observe then, that if we can prove that the system S is consistent (i.e. the statement in the hypothesis of c), then we have proved that p is not provable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] But this is a contradiction since by the 1st Incompleteness Theorem, this sentence (i.e. what is implied in the sentence c, ""p" is not provable") is what we construct to be unprovable.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] Notice that this is why we require formalizing the first Incompleteness Theorem in S: to prove the 2nd Incompleteness Theorem, we obtain a contradiction with the 1st Incompleteness Theorem which can do only by showing that the theorem holds in S.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] So we cannot prove that the system S is consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p01] And the 2nd Incompleteness Theorem statement follows.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] The incompleteness results affect the philosophy of mathematics, particularly versions of formalism, which use a single system of formal logic to define their principles.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] The incompleteness theorem is sometimes thought to have severe consequences for the program of logicism proposed by Gottlob Frege and Bertrand Russell, which aimed to define the natural numbers in terms of logic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Bob Hale and Crispin Wright argue that it is not a problem for logicism because the incompleteness theorems apply equally to first-order logic as they do to arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] They argue that only those who believe that the natural numbers are to be defined in terms of first order logic have this problem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Many logicians believe that Gödel's incompleteness theorems struck a fatal blow to David Hilbert's second problem, which asked for a finitary consistency proof for mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] The second incompleteness theorem, in particular, is often viewed as making the problem impossible.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Not all mathematicians agree with this analysis, however, and the status of Hilbert's second problem is not yet decided (see "Modern viewpoints on the status of the problem").
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Lucas and physicist Roger Penrose have debated what, if anything, Gödel's incompleteness theorems imply about human intelligence.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Much of the debate centers on whether the human mind is equivalent to a Turing machine, or by the Church–Turing thesis, any finite machine at all.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] If it is, and if the machine is consistent, then Gödel's incompleteness theorems would apply to it.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Putnam (1960) suggested that while Gödel's theorems cannot be applied to humans, since they make mistakes and are therefore inconsistent, it may be applied to the human faculty of science or mathematics in general.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Assuming that it is consistent, either its consistency cannot be proved or it cannot be represented by a Turing machine.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Wigderson (2010) has proposed that the concept of mathematical "knowability" should be based on computational complexity rather than logical decidability.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Douglas Hofstadter, in his books *Gödel, Escher, Bach* and *I Am a Strange Loop*, cites Gödel's theorems as an example of what he calls a *strange loop*, a hierarchical, self-referential structure existing within an axiomatic formal system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] He argues that this is the same kind of structure that gives rise to consciousness, the sense of "I", in the human mind.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Hofstadter argues that a strange loop in a sufficiently complex formal system can give rise to a "downward" or "upside-down" causality, a situation in which the normal hierarchy of cause-and-effect is flipped upside-down.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Although Gödel's theorems are usually studied in the context of classical logic, they also have a role in the study of paraconsistent logic and of inherently contradictory statements (*dialetheia*).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Priest (1984, 2006) argues that replacing the notion of formal proof in Gödel's theorem with the usual notion of informal proof can be used to show that naive mathematics is inconsistent, and uses this as evidence for dialetheism.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] The cause of this inconsistency is the inclusion of a truth predicate for a system within the language of the system.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Shapiro (2002) gives a more mixed appraisal of the applications of Gödel's theorems to dialetheism.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Appeals and analogies are sometimes made to the incompleteness of theorems in support of arguments that go beyond mathematics and logic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Several authors have commented negatively on such extensions and interpretations, including Franzén (2005), Raatikainen (2005), Sokal & Bricmont (1999); and Stangroom & Benson (2006).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Sokal & Bricmont (1999) and Stangroom & Benson (2006), for example, quote from Rebecca Goldstein's comments on the disparity between Gödel's avowed Platonism and the anti-realist uses to which his ideas are sometimes put.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Sokal & Bricmont (1999) criticize Régis Debray's invocation of the theorem in the context of sociology; Debray has defended this use as metaphorical (ibid.).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] After Gödel published his proof of the completeness theorem as his doctoral thesis in 1929, he turned to a second problem for his habilitation.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] His original goal was to obtain a positive solution to Hilbert's second problem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] At the time, theories of natural numbers and real numbers similar to second-order arithmetic were known as "analysis", while theories of natural numbers alone were known as "arithmetic".
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel was not the only person working on the consistency problem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Ackermann had published a flawed consistency proof for analysis in 1925, in which he attempted to use the method of ε-substitution originally developed by Hilbert.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Later that year, von Neumann was able to correct the proof for a system of arithmetic without any axioms of induction.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] By 1928, Ackermann had communicated a modified proof to Bernays; this modified proof led Hilbert to announce his belief in 1929 that the consistency of arithmetic had been demonstrated and that a consistent proof of analysis would likely soon follow.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] After the publication of the incompleteness theorems showed that Ackermann's modified proof must be erroneous, von Neumann produced a concrete example showing that its main technique was unsound.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] In the course of his research, Gödel discovered that, although a sentence asserting its falsehood leads to paradox, a sentence that asserts its non-provability does not.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] In particular, Gödel was aware of the result later called Tarski's indefinability theorem, although he never published it.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel announced his first incompleteness theorem to Carnap, Feigl, and Waismann on August 26, 1930; all four would attend the Second Conference on the Epistemology of the Exact Sciences, a key conference in Königsberg the following week.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] The 1930 Königsberg conference was a joint meeting of three academic societies, with many of the key logicians of the time in attendance.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Carnap, Heyting, and von Neumann delivered one-hour addresses on the mathematical philosophies of logicism, intuitionism, and formalism, respectively.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] The conference also included Hilbert's retirement address, as he was leaving his position at the University of Göttingen.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Hilbert used the speech to argue his belief that all mathematical problems can be solved.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] This speech quickly became known as a summary of Hilbert's beliefs on mathematics (its final six words, "*Wir müssen wissen.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Wir werden wissen!*", were used as Hilbert's epitaph in 1943).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Although Gödel was likely in attendance for Hilbert's address, the two never met face to face.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel announced his first incompleteness theorem at a roundtable discussion session on the third day of the conference.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] The announcement drew little attention apart from that of von Neumann, who pulled Gödel aside for a conversation.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Later that year, working independently with knowledge of the first incompleteness theorem, von Neumann obtained a proof of the second incompleteness theorem, which he announced to Gödel in a letter dated November 20, 1930.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel had independently obtained the second incompleteness theorem and included it in his submitted manuscript, which was received by *Monatshefte für Mathematik* on November 17, 1930.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel's paper was published in the *Monatshefte* in 1931 under the title "Über formal unentscheidbare Sätze der Principia Mathematica und verwandter Systeme I" ("On Formally Undecidable Propositions in Principia Mathematica and Related Systems I").
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] As the title implies, Gödel originally planned to publish a second part of the paper in the next volume of the *Monatshefte*; the prompt acceptance of the first paper was one reason he changed his plans.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel gave a series of lectures on his theorems at Princeton in 1933–1934 to an audience that included Church, Kleene, and Rosser.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] By this time, Gödel had grasped that the key property his theorems required is that the system must be effective (at the time, the term "general recursive" was used).
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Rosser proved in 1936 that the hypothesis of ω-consistency, which was an integral part of Gödel's original proof, could be replaced by simple consistency if the Gödel sentence was changed appropriately.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] These developments left the incompleteness theorems in essentially their modern form.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gentzen published his consistency proof for first-order arithmetic in 1936.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Hilbert accepted this proof as "finitary" although (as Gödel's theorem had already shown) it cannot be formalized within the system of arithmetic that is being proved consistent.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] The impact of the incompleteness theorems on Hilbert's program was quickly realized.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Bernays included a full proof of the incompleteness theorems in the second volume of *Grundlagen der Mathematik* (1939), along with additional results of Ackermann on the ε-substitution method and Gentzen's consistency proof of arithmetic.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] This was the first full published proof of the second incompleteness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Finsler (1926) used a version of Richard's paradox to construct an expression that was false but unprovable in a particular, informal framework he had developed.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel was unaware of this paper when he proved the incompleteness theorems (Collected Works Vol.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Finsler wrote to Gödel in 1931 to inform him about this paper, which Finsler felt had priority for an incompleteness theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Finsler's methods did not rely on formalized provability and had only a superficial resemblance to Gödel's work.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel read the paper but found it deeply flawed, and his response to Finsler laid out concerns about the lack of formalization.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Finsler continued to argue for his philosophy of mathematics, which eschewed formalization, for the remainder of his career.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] In September 1931, Ernst Zermelo wrote to Gödel to announce what he described as an "essential gap" in Gödel's argument.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] In October, Gödel replied with a 10-page letter, where he pointed out that Zermelo mistakenly assumed that the notion of truth in a system is definable in that system; it is not true in general by Tarski's undefinability theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] However, Zermelo did not relent and published his criticisms in print with "a rather scathing paragraph on his young competitor".
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel decided that pursuing the matter further was pointless, and Carnap agreed.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Much of Zermelo's subsequent work was related to logic stronger than first-order logic, with which he hoped to show both the consistency and categoricity of mathematical theories.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Gödel was a member of the Vienna Circle during the period in which Wittgenstein's early ideal language philosophy and Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus dominated the circle's thinking.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] There has been some controversy about whether Wittgenstein misunderstood the incompleteness theorem or just expressed himself unclearly.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Writings in Gödel's Nachlass express the belief that Wittgenstein misread his ideas.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Multiple commentators have read Wittgenstein as misunderstanding Gödel, although Floyd & Putnam (2000) as well as Priest (2004) have provided textual readings arguing that most commentary misunderstands Wittgenstein.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] On their release, Bernays, Dummett, and Kreisel wrote separate reviews on Wittgenstein's remarks, all of which were extremely negative.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] The unanimity of this criticism caused Wittgenstein's remarks on the incompleteness theorems to have little impact on the logic community.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] In 1972, Gödel stated: "Has Wittgenstein lost his mind?
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Since the publication of Wittgenstein's *Nachlass* in 2000, a series of papers in philosophy have sought to evaluate whether the original criticism of Wittgenstein's remarks was justified.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Floyd & Putnam (2000) argue that Wittgenstein had a more complete understanding of the incompleteness theorem than was previously assumed.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] They are particularly concerned with the interpretation of a Gödel sentence for an ω-inconsistent system as saying "I am not provable", since the system has no models in which the provability predicate corresponds to actual provability.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Rodych (2003) argues that their interpretation of Wittgenstein is not historically justified.
[src:logic-foundations/gödel-s-incompleteness-theorems-p02] Berto (2009) explores the relationship between Wittgenstein's writing and theories of paraconsistent logic.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A **mathematical proof** is a deductive argument for a mathematical statement, showing that the stated assumptions logically guarantee the conclusion.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The argument may use other previously established statements, such as theorems; but every proof can, in principle, be constructed using only certain basic or original assumptions known as axioms, along with the accepted rules of inference.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Proofs are examples of exhaustive deductive reasoning that establish logical certainty, to be distinguished from empirical arguments or non-exhaustive inductive reasoning that establish "reasonable expectation".
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Presenting many cases in which the statement holds is not enough for a proof, which must demonstrate that the statement is true in *all* possible cases.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A proposition that has not been proved but is believed to be true is known as a conjecture, or a hypothesis if frequently used as an assumption for further mathematical work.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Proofs employ logic expressed in mathematical symbols, along with natural language that usually admits some ambiguity.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In most mathematical literature, proofs are written in terms of rigorous informal logic.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Purely formal proofs, written fully in symbolic language without the involvement of natural language, are considered in proof theory.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The distinction between formal and informal proofs has led to much examination of current and historical mathematical practice, quasi-empiricism in mathematics, and so-called folk mathematics, oral traditions in the mainstream mathematical community or in other cultures.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The philosophy of mathematics is concerned with the role of language and logic in proofs, and mathematics as a language.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The word *proof* derives from the Latin *probare* 'to test'; related words include English *probe*, *probation*, and *probability*, as well as Spanish *probar* 'to taste' (sometimes 'to touch' or 'to test'), Italian *provare* 'to try', and German *probieren* 'to try'.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The legal term *probity* means authority or credibility, the power of testimony to prove facts when given by persons of reputation or status.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Plausibility arguments using heuristic devices such as pictures and analogies preceded strict mathematical proof.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] It is likely that the idea of demonstrating a conclusion first arose in connection with geometry, which originated in practical problems of land measurement.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The development of mathematical proof is primarily the product of ancient Greek mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Thales (624–546 BCE) and Hippocrates of Chios (c.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] 470–410 BCE) gave some of the first known proofs of theorems in geometry.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Eudoxus (408–355 BCE) and Theaetetus (417–369 BCE) formulated theorems but did not prove them.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Aristotle (384–322 BCE) said definitions should describe the concept being defined in terms of other concepts already known.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Mathematical proof was revolutionized by Euclid (300 BCE), who introduced the axiomatic method still in use today.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] It starts with undefined terms and axioms, propositions concerning the undefined terms which are assumed to be self-evidently true (from Greek *axios* 'something worthy').
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] From this basis, the method proves theorems using deductive logic.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] *Euclid's Elements* was read by anyone who was considered educated in the West until the middle of the 20th century.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In addition to theorems of geometry, such as the Pythagorean theorem, the *Elements* also covers number theory, including a proof that the square root of two is irrational and a proof that there are infinitely many prime numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Further advances also took place in medieval Islamic mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In the 10th century, the Iraqi mathematician Al-Hashimi worked with numbers as such, called "lines" but not necessarily considered as measurements of geometric objects, to prove algebraic propositions concerning multiplication, division, etc., including the existence of irrational numbers.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] An inductive proof for arithmetic progressions was introduced in the *Al-Fakhri* (1000) by Al-Karaji, who used it to prove the binomial theorem and properties of Pascal's triangle.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Modern proof theory treats proofs as inductively defined data structures, not requiring an assumption that axioms are "true" in any sense.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] This allows parallel mathematical theories as formal models of a given intuitive concept, based on alternate sets of axioms, for example axiomatic set theory and non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] As practiced, a proof is expressed in natural language and is a rigorous argument intended to convince the audience of the truth of a statement.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The standard of rigor is not absolute and has varied throughout history.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A proof can be presented differently depending on the intended audience.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] To gain acceptance, a proof has to meet communal standards of rigor; an argument considered vague or incomplete may be rejected.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The concept of proof is formalized in the field of mathematical logic.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A formal proof is written in a formal language instead of natural language.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A formal proof is a sequence of formulas in a formal language, starting with an assumption, and with each subsequent formula a logical consequence of the preceding ones.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] This definition makes the concept of proof amenable to study.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Indeed, the field of proof theory studies formal proofs and their properties, the most famous and surprising being that almost all axiomatic systems can generate certain undecidable statements not provable within the system.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The definition of a formal proof is intended to capture the concept of proofs as written in the practice of mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The soundness of this definition amounts to the belief that a published proof can, in principle, be converted into a formal proof.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] However, outside the field of automated proof assistants, this is rarely done in practice.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A classic question in philosophy asks whether mathematical proofs are analytic or synthetic.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Kant, who introduced the analytic–synthetic distinction, believed mathematical proofs are synthetic, whereas Quine argued in his 1951 "Two Dogmas of Empiricism" that such a distinction is untenable.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Proofs may be admired for their mathematical beauty.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The mathematician Paul Erdős was known for describing proofs which he found to be particularly elegant as coming from "The Book", a hypothetical tome containing the most beautiful method(s) of proving each theorem.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The book *Proofs from THE BOOK*, published in 2003, is devoted to presenting 32 proofs its editors find particularly pleasing.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In direct proof, the conclusion is established by logically combining the axioms, definitions, and earlier theorems.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Hence, the sum of any two even integers is even.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] This proof uses the definition of even integers, the integer properties of closure under addition and multiplication, and the distributive property.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Despite its name, mathematical induction is a method of deduction, not a form of inductive reasoning.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In proof by mathematical induction, a single "base case" is proved, and an "induction rule" is proved that establishes that any arbitrary case implies the next case.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Since in principle the induction rule can be applied repeatedly (starting from the proven base case), it follows that all (usually infinitely many) cases are provable.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] This avoids having to prove each case individually.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A variant of mathematical induction is proof by infinite descent, which can be used, for example, to prove the irrationality of the square root of two.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] For example, we can prove by induction that all positive integers of the form 2*n* − 1 are odd.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] to an odd number results in an odd number.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The shorter phrase "proof by induction" is often used instead of "proof by mathematical induction".
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Proof by contraposition infers the statement "if *p* then *q*" by establishing the logically equivalent contrapositive statement: "if *not q* then *not p*".
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In proof by contradiction, also known by the Latin phrase *reductio ad absurdum* (by reduction to the absurd), it is shown that if some statement is assumed true, a logical contradiction occurs, hence the statement must be false.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Since the expression on the left is an integer multiple of 2, the right expression is by definition divisible by 2.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] are both even, they have 2 as a common factor.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] To paraphrase: if one could write ${\sqrt {2}}$ as a fraction, this fraction could never be written in lowest terms, since 2 could always be factored from numerator and denominator.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Proof by construction, or proof by example, is the construction of a concrete example with a property to show that something having that property exists.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Joseph Liouville, for instance, proved the existence of transcendental numbers by constructing an explicit example.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] It can also be used to construct a counterexample to disprove a proposition that all elements have a certain property.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In proof by exhaustion, the conclusion is established by dividing it into a finite number of cases and proving each one separately.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The number of cases sometimes can become very large.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] For example, the first proof of the four color theorem was a proof by exhaustion with 1,936 cases.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] This proof was controversial because the majority of the cases were checked by a computer program, not by hand.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A closed chain inference shows that a collection of statements are pairwise equivalent.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The pairwise equivalence of the statements then results from the transitivity of the material conditional.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A probabilistic proof is one in which an example is shown to exist, with certainty, by using methods of probability theory.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Probabilistic proof, like proof by construction, is one of many ways to prove existence theorems.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In the probabilistic method, one seeks an object having a given property, starting with a large set of candidates.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] One assigns a certain probability for each candidate to be chosen, and then proves that there is a non-zero probability that a chosen candidate will have the desired property.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] This does not specify which candidates have the property, but the probability could not be positive without at least one.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A probabilistic proof is not to be confused with an argument that a theorem is 'probably' true, a 'plausibility argument'.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The work toward the Collatz conjecture shows how far plausibility is from genuine proof, as does the disproof of the Mertens conjecture.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A combinatorial proof establishes the equivalence of different expressions by showing that they count the same object in different ways.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Often a bijection between two sets is used to show that the expressions for their two sizes are equal.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Alternatively, a double counting argument provides two different expressions for the size of a single set, again showing that the two expressions are equal.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A nonconstructive proof establishes that a mathematical object with a certain property exists—without explaining how such an object can be found.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Often, this takes the form of a proof by contradiction in which the nonexistence of the object is proved to be impossible.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In contrast, a constructive proof establishes that a particular object exists by providing a method of finding it.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The following famous example of a nonconstructive proof shows that there exist two irrational numbers *a* and *b* such that $a^{b}$ is a rational number.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] This proof uses that ${\sqrt {2}}$ is irrational (an easy proof is known since Euclid), but not that ${\sqrt {2}}^{\sqrt {2}}$ is irrational (this is true, but the proof is not elementary).
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The expression "statistical proof" may be used technically or colloquially in areas of pure mathematics, such as involving cryptography, chaotic series, and probabilistic number theory or analytic number theory.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] It is less commonly used to refer to a mathematical proof in the branch of mathematics known as mathematical statistics.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] See also the "Statistical proof using data" section below.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Until the twentieth century it was assumed that any proof could, in principle, be checked by a competent mathematician to confirm its validity.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] However, automated theorem provers and proof assistants are now used to prove theorems and carry out calculations that are too long for any human or team of humans to check; the first proof of the four color theorem is an example of a computer-assisted proof.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Some mathematicians are concerned that the possibility of an error in a computer program or a run-time error in its calculations calls the validity of such computer-assisted proofs into question.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In practice, the chances of an error invalidating a computer-assisted proof can be reduced by incorporating redundancy and self-checks into calculations, and by developing multiple independent approaches and programs.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Errors can never be completely ruled out in case of verification of a proof by humans either, especially if the proof contains natural language and requires deep mathematical insight to uncover the potential hidden assumptions and fallacies involved.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A statement that is neither provable nor disprovable from a set of axioms is called undecidable (from those axioms).
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] One example is the parallel postulate, which is neither provable nor refutable from the remaining axioms of Euclidean geometry.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Mathematicians have shown there are many statements that are neither provable nor disprovable in Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the axiom of choice (ZFC), the standard system of set theory in mathematics (assuming that ZFC is consistent); see List of statements undecidable in ZFC.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Gödel's (first) incompleteness theorem shows that many axiom systems of mathematical interest will have undecidable statements.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] While early mathematicians such as Eudoxus of Cnidus did not use proofs, from Euclid to the foundational mathematics developments of the late 19th and 20th centuries, proofs were an essential part of mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] With the increase in computing power in the 1960s, significant work began to be done investigating mathematical objects beyond the proof-theorem framework, in experimental mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Early pioneers of these methods intended the work ultimately to be resolved into a classical proof-theorem framework, e.g. the early development of fractal geometry, which was ultimately so resolved.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A particular way of organizing a proof using two parallel columns is often used as a mathematical exercise in elementary geometry classes in the United States.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The proof is written as a series of lines in two columns.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] In each line, the left-hand column contains a proposition, while the right-hand column contains a brief explanation of how the corresponding proposition in the left-hand column is either an axiom, a hypothesis, or can be logically derived from previous propositions.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] The left-hand column is typically headed "Statements" and the right-hand column is typically headed "Reasons".
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Sometimes, the abbreviation *"Q.E.D."* is written to indicate the end of a proof.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] This abbreviation stands for *"quod erat demonstrandum"*, which is Latin for *"that which was to be demonstrated"*.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] A more common alternative is to use a square or a rectangle, such as □ or ∎, known as a "tombstone" or "Halmos" after its eponym Paul Halmos.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Often, "which was to be shown" is verbally stated when writing "QED", "□", or "∎" during an oral presentation.
[src:logic-foundations/mathematical-proof] Unicode explicitly provides the "end of proof" character, U+220E (∎) (220E(hex) = 8718(dec)).
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] In logic, a **predicate** is a non-logical symbol that represents a property or a relation, though, formally, does not need to represent anything at all.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] For instance, in the first-order formula $P(a)$ , the symbol P is a predicate that applies to the individual constant a which evaluates to either true or false.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] Similarly, in the formula $R(a,b)$ , the symbol R is a predicate that applies to the individual constants a and b .
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] Predicates are considered a primitive notion of first-order, and higher-order logic and are therefore not defined in terms of other more basic concepts.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] The term derives from the grammatical term "predicate", meaning a word or phrase that represents a property or relation.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] In the semantics of logic, predicates are interpreted as relations.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] For instance, in a standard semantics for first-order logic, the formula $R(a,b)$ would be true on an interpretation if the entities denoted by a and b stand in the relation denoted by R .
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] Since predicates are non-logical symbols, they can denote different relations depending on the interpretation given to them.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] While first-order logic only includes predicates that apply to individual objects, other logics may allow predicates that apply to collections of objects defined by other predicates.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] Strictly speaking, a predicate does not need to be given any interpretation, so long as its syntactic properties are well-defined.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] For example, equality may be understood solely through its reflexive and substitution properties (cf.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] Other properties can be derived from these, and they are sufficient for proving theorems in mathematics.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] Similarly, set membership can be understood solely through the axioms of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory.
[src:logic-foundations/predicate-logic] A predicate is a statement or mathematical assertion that contains variables, sometimes referred to as predicate variables, and may be true or false depending on those variables’ value or values.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Although it is quite freely used in mathematical proofs, not every school of mathematical thought accepts this kind of nonconstructive proof.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] This argument form traces back to Ancient Greek philosophy and has been used throughout history in both formal mathematical and philosophical reasoning, as well as in debate.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] In mathematics, the technique is called proof by contradiction.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] In formal logic, this technique is captured by an inference rule for *reductio ad absurdum*.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] More broadly, proof by contradiction is any form of argument that establishes a statement by arriving at a contradiction, even when the initial assumption is not the negation of the statement to be proved.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] In this general sense, proof by contradiction is also known as **indirect proof**, **proof by assuming the opposite**, and *reductio ad impossibile*.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] The first example argues that denial of the premise would result in a ridiculous conclusion, against the evidence of our senses (empirical evidence).
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] The second example is a mathematical proof by contradiction (also known as an indirect proof), which argues that the denial of the premise would result in a logical contradiction (⁠ $q/2$ ⁠ is both smaller and not smaller than ⁠ q ⁠).
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] We assume *P* to be false, i.e., we assume *¬P*.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] It is then shown that *¬P* implies falsehood.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] This is typically accomplished by deriving two mutually contradictory assertions, *Q* and *¬Q*, and appealing to the law of noncontradiction.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Since assuming *P* to be false leads to a contradiction, it is concluded that *P* is in fact true.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] An important special case is the existence proof by contradiction: in order to demonstrate that an object with a given property exists, we derive a contradiction from the assumption that all objects satisfy the negation of the property.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Greek mathematicians proved fundamental propositions using *reductio ad absurdum*.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Euclid of Alexandria (mid-4th – mid-3rd centuries BCE) and Archimedes of Syracuse (c.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] The earlier dialogues of Plato (424–348 BCE), relating the discourses of Socrates, raised the use of *reductio* arguments to a formal dialectical method (*elenchus*), also called the Socratic method.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Typically, Socrates' opponent would make what would seem to be an innocuous assertion.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] In response, Socrates, via a step-by-step train of reasoning, bringing in other background assumptions, would make the person admit that the assertion resulted in an absurd or contradictory conclusion, forcing him to abandon his assertion and adopt a position of aporia.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Elenctic refutation depends on a dichotomous thesis, one that may be divided into exactly two mutually exclusive parts, only one of which may be true.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Then Socrates goes on to demonstrate the contrary of the commonly accepted part using the law of non-contradiction.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Socrates secures his interlocutor's agreement to further premises, for example, "Courage is a fine thing" and "Ignorant endurance is not a fine thing".
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Socrates then argues, and the interlocutor agrees, that these further premises imply the contrary of the original thesis, in this case, it leads to: "courage is not endurance of the soul".
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Socrates then claims that he has shown that his interlocutor's thesis is false and that its negation is true.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] The technique was also a focus of the work of Aristotle (384–322 BCE), particularly in his *Prior Analytics* where he referred to it as demonstration to the impossible (Ancient Greek: ἡ εἰς τὸ ἀδύνατον ἀπόδειξις, lit.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] 'demonstration to the impossible', 62b).
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Another example of this technique is found in the sorites paradox, where it was argued that if 1,000,000 grains of sand formed a heap, and removing one grain from a heap left it a heap, then a single grain of sand (or even no grains) forms a heap.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Much of Madhyamaka Buddhist philosophy centers on showing how various essentialist ideas have absurd conclusions through *reductio ad absurdum* arguments (known as *prasaṅga*, "consequence" in Sanskrit).
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] In the Mūlamadhyamakakārikā, Nāgārjuna's *reductio ad absurdum* arguments are used to show that any theory of substance or essence was unsustainable and therefore, phenomena (*dharmas*) such as change, causality, and sense perception were empty (*sunya*) of any essential existence.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] In 13:5, Nagarjuna wishes to demonstrate consequences of the presumption that things essentially, or inherently, exist, pointing out that if a "young man" exists in himself then it follows he cannot grow old (because he would no longer be a "young man").
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] As we attempt to separate the man from his properties (youth), we find that everything is subject to momentary change, and are left with nothing beyond the merely arbitrary convention that such entities as "young man" depend upon.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] And because an old man does not grow old either.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Contemporary philosophers have also utilized appeals to the *reductio ad absurdum* argument within their respective scholarly works.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Aristotle clarified the connection between contradiction and falsity in his principle of non-contradiction, which states that a proposition cannot be both true and false.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] That is, a proposition Q and its negation $\lnot Q$ (not-*Q*) cannot both be true.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Therefore, if a proposition and its negation are both entailed by a premise, the premise is false.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] This technique is the most common way of reaching a contradiction in mathematical arguments.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Another way to justify the principle is to derive it from the law of the excluded middle, as follows.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] 2. if *¬P* holds, then we derive falsehood by applying the law of noncontradiction to *¬P* and *¬¬P*, after which the principle of explosion allows us to conclude *P*.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] It turns out that, conversely, proof by contradiction can be used to derive the law of excluded middle.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Formally these are not the same, as refutation by contradiction applies only when the proposition to be proved is negated, whereas proof by contradiction may be applied to any proposition whatsoever.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] In classical logic, where P and $\neg \neg P$ may be freely interchanged, the distinction is largely obscured.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Thus in mathematical practice, both principles are referred to as "proof by contradiction".
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] In intuitionistic logic proof by contradiction is not generally valid, although some particular instances can be derived.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] In contrast, proof of negation and principle of noncontradiction are both intuitionistically valid.
[src:logic-foundations/proof-by-contradiction] Brouwer–Heyting–Kolmogorov interpretation of proof by contradiction gives the following intuitionistic validity condition: if there is no method for establishing that a proposition is false, then there is a method for establishing that the proposition is true.
